<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     08-12 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juror Is Dismissed For Sleeping In Night Stalker Deliberations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 13th day of jury deliberations in the
``Night Stalker'' trial was interrupted Friday when the judge
dismissed a juror for sleeping and ordered the panel to start all
over again.
   An alternate juror was chosen to replace the sleeping juror in
the complex case involving 13 murders and 30 felonies committed
during the summer of l985. Jurors heard six months of testimony
after six months of jury selection.
   Richard Ramirez, a 29-year-old drifter from El Paso, Texas, is
accused of being the devil-worshipping ``Night Stalker'' who raped,
murdered and robbed victims in a rampage that terrified Southern
California.
   Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin said he and defense
lawyer Ray Clark were summoned Friday to the courtroom of Superior
Court Judge Michael Tynan after the jury foreman sent a note saying
that one juror had been seen sleeping at the deliberation table.
   Tynan interviewed the foreman who said two other jurors had
reported seeing the man in question nodding off and snoring in the
deliberation room.
   After a brief discussion with attorneys, Tynan summoned the
juror and told him he was being dismissed for sleeping. The juror
did not protest.
   The judge then brought the entire panel into the courtroom. He
told them not to speculate on why the juror was being dismissed and
instructed them to begin their talks anew with the alternate
filling the dismissed juror's place.
   Halpin said it was impossible to tell how long it would take now
for the jury to reach a unanimous decision on the 43 counts
involved.
   Earlier this week, the jury returned to the courtroom to ask for
a repeat of testimony involving Ramirez' dental problems. It was
the first time they had asked for testimony to be read back since
they began deliberating July 26.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
