<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CrackCall     08-12 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Crack Call,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Nab Suspected Dealer Who Calls 911 for Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HATTIESBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected crack dealer curious about
a police round-up called a 911 emergency number to ask if
authorities were looking for him. When he hung up, he had his
answer _ officers were at his door.
   Police said James Earl Mays, 33, of Forrest County telephoned
the police emergency line on Thursday night to ask about a report
he heard on the street _ a grand jury had indicted 101 people
suspected of dealing crack and police were looking for them.
   A computerized system flashed the address from which Mays was
telephoning, and officers sped to the house and arrested him, a
sheriff's office spokesman said.
   The indictments were issued Thursday, and by Friday afternoon
officers had arrested more than 50 people accused of selling crack
to undercover agents working with the Metro Narcotics Task Force.
   District Attorney Glenn White said arraignments would be held
Aug. 25. The investigation began early this year, authorities said.
</TEXT>
