<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--France-Angels     08-12 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--France-Angels,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group to Start Setting Up Parisian Branch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Guardian Angels intend to set up a subway
patrol in Paris despite opposition from local officials, one of the
group's leaders says.
   Lisa Sliwa completed a five-day tour of the subway system on
Friday and told reporters she would return in September to recruit
and train French Guardian Angels.
   ``We are really needed here,'' said Ms. Sliwa, who wore the red
beret and white T-shirt that the New York-based group has adopted
as a uniform.
   The Paris transit authority and police unions have said they
oppose a Guardian Angel patrol.
   ``We are completely opposed to those who act as a militia or
other police force,'' said a statement issued Monday by the transit
authority.
   Ms. Sliwa said she had since met with police and transit
authority officials and, while not getting their approval, plans to
go ahead with setting up a subway patrol. ``We are not a militia,''
she said.
   She said the Guardian Angels, founded in 1979, patrol subways in
44 American cities, as well as in London, Montreal and Toronto.
</TEXT>
