<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthSentence     08-12 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Sentence,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Sentence Could Have Been Harsher Under Federal Guidelines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legal publication says Oliver North could
have been sentenced to more than 4{ years in prison if federal
sentencing guidelines had been applied to his Iran-Contra
conviction.
   However, the guidelines that recommend ranges of possible
sentences to judges weren't applied in the North case because they
cover only federal crimes committed after Nov. 1, 1987.
   The editors of the Federal Sentencing Reporter, a non-profit
publication circulated among federal judges, probation officers,
law professors and lawyers, concluded North could have been
sentenced under the guidelines to 21 to 57 months in prison.
   North was convicted of aiding and abetting obstruction of
Congress, destroying government documents and accepting an illegal
gratuity while working at the White House in 1986.
   He was fined, put on probation and ordered to do community
service _ but was sentenced to no jail time. North began his
community service work this week.
   The ranges ``sketch possible avenues guideline sentencing might
have taken,'' Marc Miller of Atlanta's Emory University Law School
and Daniel J. Freed of Yale University Law School said in their
analysis.
   If North's had been a guidelines case, U.S. District Court Judge
Gerhard Gesell still could have imposed no jail time but
prosecutors would have been able to appeal.
   Under the guidelines, ``there is a degree of flexibility, but
the challenge for the judge is to persuasively explain why there is
a substantial departure,'' Miller said Friday in an interview.
   ``When the appeals courts find the explanations unpersuasive,
they've reversed sentences.''
   The length of a recommended sentence under the guidelines in the
North case would depend partly on a judge deciding whether the
former White House aide substantially interfered with the
administration of justice.
   Other factors would be the value assigned to classified
documents that North destroyed, whether he was a major or minor
participant in the crime of aiding the obstruction of Congress and
whether he was considered to be in a high-level decision-making
capacity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
