<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Shoreham     08-12 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shoreham,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Joins Shoreham Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department, saying New York's
Shoreham nuclear power plant is ``safe, efficient and
much-needed,'' is joining in a lawsuit to prevent the plant from
being dismantled.
   The intervention in a state court came on behalf of the Energy
Department, which has strongly opposed the shutdown of the
813-megawatt plant on Long Island.
   W. Henson Moore, deputy energy secretary, said the state, in its
approval of the dismantling plan, had not adequately considered the
impact on the environment.
   The Justice Department argues that the New York Power Authority
and the state Public Service Commission should have prepared formal
environmental impact statements before approving the plan.
   The plant, Moore said, is ``safe, efficient and much-needed,''
adding that its closure would require the region to rely more
heavily on fossil fuel. Those fuels, he said, will have ``adverse
environmental consequences'' through the increased release of
chemicals that contribute to acid rain and global warming.
   Some Long Island residents and a group called Scientists and
Engineers for Secure Energy filed the suit against the plant.
   The Bush administration previously has made clear its opposition
to the closing of the $5.5 billion plant completed in 1985 and
licensed last year. It has yet to produce any commercial
electricity.
   State and local officials contend the plant should not be
allowed to operate because evacuation of the area 50 miles east of
New York City would be impossible.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo plans to meet with President Bush next
week to discuss White House opposition to the plant being torn down.
</TEXT>
