<FIRST>r w PM-Nofziger     08-12 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nofziger,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Move to Reinstate Former Reagan Aide's Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors want a federal appeals court to
reconsider its decision to overturn the illegal lobbying conviction
against former White House aide Lyn Nofziger.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals panel ``undermined critical
provisions of the Ethics in Government Act'' when it ruled June 27
that Nofziger's conviction must be set aside, prosecutors said in
court papers filed Friday.
   The office of independent counsel James McKay asked the court to
grant a rehearing before the three-member panel or set the case for
rehearing by all 10 members of the appeals court.
   Nofziger was convicted Feb. 11, 1988, on three counts of
lobbying top presidential aides on behalf of private clients
shortly after he left the Reagan White House.
   Prosecutors say the lobbying violated a one-year ethics law ban
against lobbying former government colleagues.
   But the appeals panel, in a 2-1 ruling, said that to get a
conviction, prosecutors were required to show that Nofziger knew he
was lobbying his former colleagues on matters in which the White
House had a ``direct and substantial interest.''
   Prosecutors maintain the law required only that they show
Nofziger intended to influence the officials on those matters.
   One of Nofziger's lawyers, Lawrence Barcella, said the
prosecution arguments present ``absolutely nothing new'' and there
is ``no reason to disturb'' the appeals court decision.
   The lobbying Nofziger performed was for the scandal-plagued
Wedtech Corp., a maritime engineers union and the manufacturer of
the Air Force's A-10 anti-tank plane.
   Nofziger, 65, was sentenced to 90 days in prison and fined
$30,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
