<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0404 08-12 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0404,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Protesters, Man Who Torched Clinic Guilty in Abortion Racketeering
Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `He and ...' to clarify that all three were found
to have conspired to violate the racketeering statute; picks up 5th graf,
`Beseda was ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two abortion protesters and a man who insisted
God told him to set fire to an abortion clinic conspired to violate
federal racketeering laws, a federal court jury ruled Friday in a
civil lawsuit.
   Curtis Beseda, already serving 20 years in a Texas federal
prison for setting fire to the Feminist Women's Health Center in
Everett, also violated the racketeering statute through arson and
extortion aimed at the abortion clinic, the jury concluded.
   The Everett clinic was burned three times between December 1983
and April 1984, then closed its doors. Beseda earlier told the jury
he had no intention of setting any fire until he heard God tell him
to do it.
   He and protesters Dottie Roberts and Sharon Codispoti, both of
Lake Stevens, were found to have conspired to violate the
racketeering statute.
   Beseda was ordered to pay $268,500 in civil damages while
Beseda, Roberts and Codispoti will share another $11,000 fine. All
damages can be trebled.
   Two other defendants, Bonnie and Michael Undseth of Snohomish,
were acquitted. Jurors in Judge Thomas Zilly's court deliberated 3{
days before reaching a verdict in the month-long trial.
   The lawsuit is only the second time the racketeering statute,
intended to fight organized crime, has been used against abortion
protesters.
   Damages will go to several clinic employees and to the Feminist
Women's Health Center of Yakima, parent clinic to the one that
burned.
   Roberts' lawyer Theresa Schrempp promised an appeal. Roberts,
holding her young grandson Timothy, said she thinks the jury was
confused by the complexity of the case, involving 52 pages of jury
instructions.
   ``It's a perversion of the First Amendment,'' she said. ``This
one's going to the Supreme Court.'' She said the plaintiffs ``won't
get anything out of me ... because I don't have anything.''
   In Philadelphia, the case that set precedent in the Seattle case
was upheld on appeal in March and defendants have asked the U.S.
Supreme Court to hear it.
   Twenty-six individuals were found guilty of multiple acts of
extortion at an abortion clinic there. The clinic was awarded
$100,000.
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs alleged Beseda and the other
defendants conspired to shut down the clinic by arson, personal and
telephone harassment of patients and staff, blocking access to and
from the clinic, picketing and helping Beseda escape to Canada.
   A successful action under the racketeering statute must show an
enterprise adversely affects interstate commerce and engages in a
pattern of racketeering, meaning a serious violation of the law
such as arson, extortion, wire fraud, robbery, kidnapping or
murder, said Edmond Tiryak, the civil rights attorney who tried the
Philadelphia case.
</TEXT>
