<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0226EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FDA-GenericDrugs     08-12 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Generic Drugs,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Revokes Two Generic Drug Approvals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is taking the
first formal action against generic drug companies being
investigated by the agency, revoking recent drug approvals of two
manufacturers.
   The revocations were issued Friday against Par Pharmaceutical
Inc. of Spring Valley, N.Y., and American Therapeutics Inc. of
Bohemia, N.Y.
   Both actions involved chlorozoxazone, the generic name for
Parafon Forte, a muscle relaxant made by Johnson &amp; Johnson. Par
received approval to market its version June 5 and ATI was granted
approval June 23.
   FDA spokesman Jeff Nesbit said the approvals were rescinded
because the reports on which they were based didn't include
``substantial deficiencies in manufacturing practices'' found
during a recent special inspection.
   The approvals were revoked Aug. 3, Nesbit said.
   Both companies disputed the legal ground on which FDA issued the
revocations.
   ``The agency just can't summarily rescind a new drug approval
without providing sponsor due process of law,'' said David Weeda, a
lawyer for ATI.
   He said the manufacturing problems cited by the FDA involved
``minor labeling and packaging deficiencies, which the company made
prompt corrective action.''
   ATI had not shipped its product when the approval was rescinded,
but Par had begun shipping, a spokeswoman said.
   ``It's not being shipped anymore, but it's not being recalled
either,'' said Par lawyer Barbara Manners. She said FDA hadn't
raised any questions about the safety of the product.
   Par and ATI are among 11 generic drug companies being
investigated by the FDA in the wake of allegations of fraud and
corruption in the generic drug industry.
   Par recently pleaded guilty to providing an improper gratuity to
an FDA employee. Par also has admitted giving the FDA false
information about one of its drugs, which it has recalled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
