<NOTE>US Condemns Syrian Role In Beirut Fighting</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is taking the unusual
step of singling out Syria for its role in the latest round of
fighting in Beirut.
   The criticism came Friday as U.S. officials continued to seek
Syrian help to obtain the release of eight American hostages held
by pro-Iranian militants in Lebanon.
   ``We again call upon Syria, an active participant in the
fighting, the Lebanese armed forces, as well as the various
Lebanese factions, for an immediate cease-fire, the lifting of all
blockades and the initiation of a dialogue for the political
reconstruction of Lebanon,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler.
   The State Department has generally refrained from singling out
the combatants by name, preferring to call for restraint by all
sides.
   The latest round of fighting in the five-month artillery war
over control of Beirut came Friday, when Syrian and Christian
gunners dueled with howitzers and rocket launchers, killing six
people.
   U.S. policy toward Syria treads a delicate balance of criticism
of the Soviet-backed government for its support of Palestinian and
Shiite terrorism and seeking to enlist its support for the
Arab-Israeli peace process and other negotiations in the volatile
region.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>No Evidence of Uncontrolled Chain Reaction: DOE</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department says investigators found
no evidence that an uncontrolled nuclear chain reaction occurred at
the Rocky Flats weapons plant near Denver.
   However, the department said Friday that plutonium was found in
situations that require ``immediate attention.'' The DOE did not
detail those situations or what would be done about them.
   Plutonium is the nuclear material recovered from weapons being
retired and reprocessed at Rocky Flats to make triggers for new
weapons. It is highly toxic.
   The question of a chain reaction arose after radioactive
isotopes of strontium and cesium, which don't occur in nature, were
found in groundwater near the plant. Some plant employees claimed
that conditions existed routinely that could lead to a chain
reaction.
   An uncontrolled chain reaction produces an explosion in a bomb
and a controlled reaction is the basis for nuclear power plants.
   Officials from the Environmental Protection Agency and state
agencies said the strontium and cesium radioactivity was so low
that it was almost undetectable, and might have been the result of
fallout from atmospheric nuclear tests of the 1950s and 1960s.
   Rocky Flats has been criticized for polluting the environment,
and the FBI has begun an investigation of past practices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>One Pentagon Official Sworn In; Another Resigns</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ford Motor Co. executive John Betti,
sworn in as the Pentagon's undersecretary of defense for
acquisition, says there will be a ``fundamental change'' in the way
the Defense Department spends its money.
   Betti has been put in charge of streamlining the agency's $150
billion-a-year purchasing bureaucracy.
   ``A fundamental change is required if we are to optimize the
overall acquisition process and provide the highest quality
products and services to the men and women in the field _ on time
and on cost,'' Betti said in a statement Friday.
   Betti had worked for Ford since 1962, most recently as executive
vice president for Ford's diversified products operation.
   Also Friday, Army Secretary John O. Marsh Jr. stepped down from
his Pentagon job after serving the longest term of any such service
secretary in the nation's history _ 8 years, 6 months and 15 days.
   He will be succeeded by Michael Stone, undersecretary of the
Army.
   However, Marsh will be back at the Pentagon on Monday as an
adviser to Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   In February, Marsh broke the record for longevity set by Thomas
Jefferson's secretary of war, Henry Dearborn, who served from 1801
to 1809, according to figures provided by the Army's office of
public affairs.
</TEXT>
