<FIRST>r p PM-BuffaloMayor Bjt   08-12 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Buffalo Mayor, Bjt,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dog Days of Summer Finds A Three-Way Dogfight for Buffalo Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politics in this working-class city have
never been pretty, and it is not surprising this summer's three-way
mayoral race has turned downright ugly.
   Mayor James Griffin has been called ``a six-pack politician.''
State Assemblyman William Hoyt was dubbed a ``silk-stocking
liberal.'' And, former chief city judge Wilbur Trammell cannot
shake the tag of being a spoiler.
   When the candidates aren't calling each other names, they have
some choice words for the reporters who cover them. Griffin said
Monday that 90 percent of the city's journalists were dishonest and
he advised them all to ``mind their own business.''
   Things began to turn nasty last week when Trammell confirmed he
was circulating petitions to qualify himself for an independent
line in the Nov. 7 general election. The move was interpreted to
mean that even if he lost the Sept. 11 Democratic primary, he would
stay in the race.
   ``Nobody controls me,'' Trammell said.
   Aides to Hoyt, who has the Democratic Party's endorsement,
blasted Trammell for being a spoiler.
   Griffin, a registered Democrat running with the Republican Party
endorsement for his fourth, four-year term as mayor, has benefited
in past campaigns from having the Democratic vote split among two
or more challengers. Polls indicate the same thing may happen this
year.
   In an emotional rebuttal of allegations that he was in the race
to help keep Griffin in office, Trammell said, ``No six-pack mayor
or silk-stocking liberal is going to defeat (me) no matter what
they try.''
   During a major snow storm that hit Buffalo in 1985, Griffin
advised residents to stay in their homes and relax with a six-pack
of beer.
   In addition, Trammell charged that Hoyt ``is in bed with Jimmy
Griffin, a bigot from day one.'' Griffin and Hoyt are white;
Trammell is black.
   Hoyt, in turn, claims that Trammell has ``zero chance'' of
winning the primary and should get out of the race. If Trammell
quit, Hoyt said his polls show that he would have enough support to
beat Griffin in a head-to-head matchup either in the primary or the
general election.
   Griffin ridiculed Hoyt for having paid $50,000 to a pollster
``just to tell him he's losing.'' Added the mayor at a news
conference, ``I could have told him that.''
   The mayor brushed aside reports that except for his monthly news
conference, he has avoided both his opponents and the media.
   The mayor said that if reporters want to cover him on the
campaign trail they should follow him around. He admitted he hasn't
been making his campaign schedule available, but said he might on
request.
</TEXT>
