<FIRST>r w PM-MurderRewards     08-12 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Murder Rewards,358</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Offers Money For Tips on Murders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 5th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Informants with tips leading to the arrest of
murder suspects will be paid up to $10,000 under a program that
District of Columbia police hope will slow a record homicide rate.
   Police Chief Isaac Fulwood, holding his first news conference
Friday, said the new reward system is based on an existing program
that pays anonymous individuals up to $1,000 for information that
leads to convictions in robbery, theft and assault cases.
   At the same time, Mayor Marion Barry said a new police overtime
plan to help slow the pace of killings probably will be scrapped
because it is too expensive.
   Fulwood said the more lucrative reward system was needed because
many district residents have become intimidated by drug-related
violence and were afraid to speak up.
   ``There is a tolerance of this. What you have to do, Washington
D.C., is get up off your ass, if you'll pardon the expression, and
call us,'' said Fulwood who, along with Barry, unveiled a poster
with photographs of 18 murder suspects.
   Later Friday, police discovered one of the suspects is already
in the city jail.
   Police have made arrests in 181 murder cases this year, Fulwood
said. Through Friday, 274 persons had been killed in the nation's
capital this year, compared with 191 at the same time last year. In
1988, a record 372 persons were killed in Washington; police blame
more than 60 percent of these slayings on drugs.
   The program is Fulwood's second attempt in a week to slow the
city's record homicide rate, which increased sharply several weeks
ago.
   On Monday, Fulwood announced that officers working between 3
p.m. and 11 p.m. _ traditionally the period of highest crime _ will
now work until 3 a.m. to help stop the murders.
   However, Barry said after the press conference that the new
overtime program likely will be abandoned because it costs too much.
   Police spokesman Lt. Reginald Smith said the new overtime
concept will be reviewed next week, and he added that cost will be
one of the factors considered.
</TEXT>
