<FIRST>u i PM-Panama Bjt   08-12 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, Bjt,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Again Detain U.S. Soldiers; Noriega Blasts Plebiscite Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian troops briefly detained American
soldiers in another confrontation between both sides, and Gen.
Manuel Noriega again indicated he has no intention of stepping down
as Panama's leader.
   Noriega today marked six years as head of the Panamanian Defense
Forces and the nation's de facto ruler.
   He said Friday that a plebiscite proposed by the opposition for
Aug. 20 on whether he should resign was tantamount to turning
Panama into ``a colony that accepts arrogance, vassalage and
indignity.''
   He spoke during a parade of thousands of troops and paramilitary
civilian units ending a 10-day exercise called ``Zap the Intruder.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in Washington on
Friday that the Bush administration ``would not rule out'' seizing
Noriega and taking him to Florida to face drug trafficking charges.
But Fitzwater said Bush was not contemplating such a move at this
time.
   The latest confrontation between Panamanian and U.S. troops
occurred in a remote area known as Curundu near the Panama Canal.
The U.S. Southern Command says the area is a military zone shared
by both countries, while the Panamanians claim it is exclusively
their domain.
   A Defense Forces patrol detained four vehicles carrying a number
of U.S. military police, and the Southern Command said it quickly
dispatched troops backed by armored cars and helicopters.
   The incident started when ``American troops went around in
civilian clothes, with their weapons, riding in private vehicles in
violation'' of the Panama Canal treaties, said Panamanian Maj.
Carlos Saldana.
   ``No country in the world can accept that units, claiming to be
part of an army, move in within its territory armed and in civilian
clothes,'' he said. ``If they tried to do this in any other nation
they would be killed like common muggers, like a vulgar thief.''
   The confrontation ended after a meeting between Panamanian and
American military officers, a Southern Command news release said.
   The command called the detentions ``unjustified.'
   ``The vehicles were freed after U.S. military officers discussed
the situation with officers of the Defense Forces,'' said a news
release issued by the command.
   Neither the Panamanians nor the Americans said how many U.S.
military police or what kind of vehicles were involved.
   Similar incidents in recent weeks coincided with Southern
Command exercises and there have been arrests on both sides.
Earlier this week, American troops blockaded Fort Amador, which
contains U.S. and Panamanian military facilities.
   U.S. officials insist they have the right to conduct exercises
under the 1977 Panama Canal treaties to assure canal security.
Noriega, however, accuses the United States of seeking to abrogate
the treaties and keep the canal, which is to be turned over to
Panama at the end of 1999.
   The United States has been trying to pressure Noriega to quit as
head of the military since two federal grand juries in Florida
indicted him on drug trafficking and money laundering charges in
February 1988. However, tactics that have included economic and
trade sanctions have failed to budge Noriega.
   Guillermo Endara, the opposition leader who proposed holding the
plebiscite on Noriega's rule, responded a few hours after Noriega's
rejection Friday by calling the leader a dictator. Endara also
accused Noriega of subservience to the United States.
   ``We never were and never will be employees of the CIA, while he
himself was one,'' Endara said in an interview.
   International observers say the opposition won the May 7
presidential election by a landslide. Noriega's regime annulled the
balloting a few days later, saying there had been vote fraud.
</TEXT>
