<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bloch     08-12 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloch Says He Was In Paris In May, Leaves Open Spying Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspended U.S. diplomat Felix Bloch said
he was in Paris the day he allegedly left a briefcase in a
restaurant for a Soviet agent, but he declined to confirm or deny
spying allegations against him.
   Bloch spoke in an Austrian television and radio interview
broadcast Friday from Washington.
   It was the second time in the past week that he declined
opportunities in interviews with Austrian media to deny the
suspicions.
   The Austrian-born diplomat, formerly the No. 2 man in Vienna's
U.S. Embassy, was suspended from the State Department on June 22.
   In Washington, the Justice Department Friday said public
disclosure of its investigation of Bloch, 54, had compromised the
government's ability to obtain evidence against him.
   ``There is no doubt that the premature disclosure of that case,
the premature disclosure that there was an ongoing investigation,
did compromise the investigation,'' department spokesman David
Runkel said without elaboration.
   No charges have been brought against Bloch. He remains under
investigation and surveillance by the FBI, and reporters have
followed him around Washington in recent days.
   ABC News has reported that on May 14, Bloch arrived in Paris
from New York and met his alleged contact for dinner. Bloch left
his briefcase under the table to be picked up by the suspected
Soviet agent, ABC said.
   Asked by Austrian TV correspondent Robert Wiesner whether he was
in Paris May 14, Bloch said after a long pause, ``Yes.''
   He declined, however, to specify whether he met Reino Gikman, a
man holding Finnish documents who regularly visited Vienna during
Bloch's 1980-87 tour in the Austrian capital. Gikman has been
identified by Austrian and U.S. authorities as a suspected KGB
agent who might have been a contact man.
   U.S. sources have said Bloch contends he only knew the man as a
stamp collector.
   When Wiesner pressed Bloch for details of the Paris trip, Bloch
said, ``I was in Paris May 14. I was in a restaurant, and there
were very many people in that restaurant, and I enjoyed the food
there very much.''
   ``Have you missed your briefcase since?'' asked Wiesner. After
another long pause, Bloch, who seemed relaxed and spoke in his
native German, said: ``No.''
   Wiesner repeatedly pressed Bloch to deny he was a spy.
   ``Why don't you just say it was all just invented?'' he asked.
   ``I could say much on this topic, but I will restrain myself,''
Bloch answered.
   By remaining silent, Wiesner noted, Bloch only heightens
suspense. ``I don't want people to feel bored during August,''
Bloch said, smiling.
   ``Are the accusations against you justified?'' Wiesner asked
again several minutes later. ``This question I cannot answer now,''
Bloch responded.
   In a much briefer interview in the current issue of the Austrian
weekly Profil, Bloch was similarly elusive. Asked why he did not
say straight out he is not a spy, he replied: ``There are
accusations, there is no proof. My guilt must be proved.''
   Bloch first accepted an invitation to visit the Washington
offices of Austria's state-run television 10 days ago, but declined
then to be interviewed.
   Wiesner said the second visit on Thursday began with Bloch
viewing cassettes of Vienna. The two chatted about Viennese
cemeteries, and then Bloch agreed to answer questions, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
