<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SculptureCity     08-12 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sculpture City,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Sweetheart City' Becomes Haven for Sculptors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two foundries and a willingness to
support public art has turned the ``Sweetheart City,'' long known
as the town with the special Valentine's Day postmark, into a haven
for sculptors.
   ``Art is in focus all the time here,'' said sculptor Fritz
White, 59, who moved to Loveland in 1978 from Cincinnati. ``We've
infiltrated the Rotary Club, the Chamber of Commerce, all kinds of
groups.''
   About 40 professional sculptors have moved to the northern
Colorado city, most of them in the past five years, and dozens of
others come to town part of the year to work with Loveland's two
foundries.
   Loveland is smitten with sculpture, displaying its own
collection along roadsides, at a sculpture park, around a new Civic
Center, and in galleries and studios around town.
   This weekend, the city is the site of one of the largest
sculpture shows in the world, Sculpture in the Park. Nearly 190
sculptors from around the nation are exhibiting work, and officials
hope the show will net the city even more than the $3.5 million it
did last year.
   Susan Hallsten McGarry, editor of Houston-based Southwest Art
magazine, called both the town and the huge sculpture show, ``a
pretty major force.... as to an actual art event that changes every
year with different people bringing new work, I don't think you can
get a broader exposure to a larger number of working sculptors
anywhere in the United States.''
   The city about 40 miles north of Denver that has struggled to
become known for something more than a place to get a special
Valentine's Day postal cancellation began its love affair with
sculpture back in 1972. Then, a local metal foundry that made parts
for General Motors began casting bronze for sculptures and soon was
accepting work from artists around the region.
   Eventually, it drew the artists themselves to Loveland, giving
many of them jobs in the business.
   A second foundry, Loveland Sculpture Works, was started by
former employees of the original foundry, Art Castings of Colorado.
   Five sculptors who had come to Loveland to be near the foundry _
George Lundeen, Dan Ostermiller, George Walbye, White and Hollis
Williford _ approached the city several years ago about helping
promote the arts.
   The result was the private Loveland High Plains Arts Council,
which raises money to buy works and then donates them to the city.
   The city does its part as well. In 1985, Loveland became the
first Colorado city to pass an ordinance setting aside 1 percent of
the construction costs of any public project over $50,000 to buy
original artwork.
   Susan Ison, director of the city's Visual Arts Commission, said
Loveland now has more than $1 million worth of art.
   In return, the influx of artists breathes new life into the
city's economy and cultural life.
   ``It's an industry in itself,'' City Manager Mike Rock said of
sculpture, which employs more than 400 people in the community of
38,200.
   Rock said Loveland's commitment to the arts has helped economic
development efforts.
   ``We can demonstrate to a company that it's a fairly
sophisticated community _ it has hometown values but an unmatched
level of art, and many community-minded citizens,'' he said.
   Downtown merchants, too, are sponsoring a sculpture park on a
prime corner to help attract more people.
   For the artists, that kind of attention and camaraderie make
Loveland an attractive place.
   White Williford moved to Loveland from Denver nine years ago to
be ``in the foundry's hip pocket.''
   Above all, Williford said, he likes the cooperative atmosphere
among Loveland sculptors.
   ``In a large city, it's more dog-eat-dog. People are less
willing to share. There's too many rats in a cage. When artists
back East come visit and we open our doors to them, they can't
believe it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
