<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Chubb-DroughtLawsuit     08-12 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chubb-Drought Lawsuit,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers Settle Drought Lawsuit as Jury Rules In Favor Of Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of farmers who were originally
denied drought insurance payments will split nearly $5 million in
compensation under an out-of-court settlement.
   As lawyers agreed to the deal, a U.S. District Court jury
awarded the farmers $40 million in damages. But the settlement
reached out of the courtroom will stand.
   In all, the farmers and Chubb Group, which joined them in their
lawsuit against Good Weather International Corp., agreed to settle
the suit for $8 million, the amount of the agent's liability
insurance.
   The farmers will collect $4.93 million and the Chubb Group of
insurance companies will collect $3.07 million. The verdict came on
the jury's second day of deliberations.
   ``We're very excited. It's further proof that the farmers had
really been taken advantage of,'' said Stanley Chesley, lawyer for
the farmers.
   Chesley said the farmers _ 8,800 in 10 states _ should be
receiving their money in about one week. He said a court-appointed
lawyer will determine the amount farmers will receive.
   Chubb, of Warren, N.J., paid $53 million to settle farmers'
claims against it, then joined the farmers' lawsuit against Good
Weather, suing to demand $77 million in damages.
   The farmers and Chubb claimed Good Weather sold more 1988
drought insurance than Chubb authorized.
   But Good Weather, based in Syosset, N.Y., maintained that Chubb
encouraged it to continue selling policies.
   The jury ruled that the company misrepresented the drought
insurance availability to the farmers. The jury also ruled that
Chubb failed to prove its cross-claims against Good Weather and did
not award anything to Chubb.
   The jury reached its verdict Friday afternoon as lawyers were in
another room at the federal courthouse working out a settlement.
   U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin had sealed the verdict until he
had a chance to confer with the lawyers.
   The farmers sued Good Weather for $20 million plus punitive
damages. The lawsuit represents farmers from Ohio, Illinois, Iowa,
Kentucky, Indiana, Tennessee, Minnesota, Michigan, Missouri and
Wisconsin.
   Good Weather's lawyer, James Moore, said Chubb was responsible
for the drought policies because the insurer encouraged Good
Weather to sell more insurance than the amount authorized in the
firms' written contract.
   After the verdict, Moore went immediately to his office and was
unavailable for comment.
   James Ringer, Chubb's lawyer, said his company was pleased with
the settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
