<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Crash     08-12 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Crash,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passengers On Derailed Train Were Headed For Work U.S. Or Visiting
Relatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUASAVE, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pacific coast whistle-stop train that
derailed and killed 112 people carried many would-be illegal aliens
who had planned to slip into the United States to find work.
   A bridge weakened by floods and torrential rain collapsed
Wednesday, pitching the train into the swirling San Rafael River 15
miles southeast of Guasave in northern Mexico.
   Survivor Cirilio Hernandez Lopez said Friday he had hoped to
cross the boarder into California to escape subsistence farming in
Etla la Villa in the southern state of Oaxaca.
   He traveled to the Sonora state beach resort of Mazatlan, and
from there took the train for the 700-mile ride to Mexicali, across
the border from Calexico, Calif.
   It would have been his first attempt to find work in the United
States.
   ``From growing corn and beans and burning oak to sell as
charcoal, I don't make anything, just enough to eat,'' said
Hernandez, 40, a Mexican of Indian descent who spoke Spanish with
difficulty.
   Hernandez said his youngest son, 16 years old, has finished
junior high school but may not be able to study further.
   ``I don't have the money for him to go to school. That's why I
was going to look for a way to earn a living,'' Hernandez said in
an interview at the Social Security Inistitute Hospital, where he
was recovering from injuries.
   He said he hoped to be released today and then would decide
whether to continue his trip to the United States.
   Sinaloa state health coordinator Humberto Gomez Campana said of
the more than 200 injured in the train derailment, 10 remained
hospitalized.
   About 400 people and four helicopters have been searching for
more victims, state security coordinator Jose Carlos de Saracho
said.
   Saracho said no more bodies were found Friday, but that the
search was to resume early today.
   Another would-be illegal alien, Benito Silva, said the $5 a day
he earned working at a taco stand in Mexico City was not enough to
feed his wife and four children and keep the eldest, a 9-year-old,
in school.
   ``I was going to cross the border. That was my intention,'' he
said.
   But the train crash left him with a leg fracture that will
require surgery, and doctors told him he would not be able to work
for at least three months.
   Many people on the train also were en route to visit relatives
or just completing summer vacations.
   People who still had not heard from relatives on the train
continued to arrive in Guasava on Friday, making the rounds of
government offices and hospitals.
   Officials buried 38 unidentified bodies in the Guasave cemetary,
their plots marked by white, nameless crosses. With the burials,
relatives had to try to identify the missing from photographs of
the bodies.
</TEXT>
