<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--NukeFine     08-12 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Nuke Fine,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility to Pay $75,000 NRC Fine For Nuke Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission issued a
$75,000 fine against the Philadelphia Electric Co. for failing to
show adequate preparation for emergencies at two nuclear units.
   ``The inspectors found that on four of the five rotating crew
shifts the shift superintendents were unable to effectively use a
classification scheme for emergency severities for certain
fast-breaking severe accidents,'' the NRC said Friday in a
statement.
   The NRC also cited a lack of aggressive management to correct
the deficiencies at the utility's Limerick reactors.
   The utility said it would not appeal the fine.
   Limerick's Unit 1 reactor is at full power. Unit 2 started on
low power Friday afternoon, while the utility hopes to restart Unit
3 in October.
</TEXT>
