<FIRST>r a PM-Railroad-Indians     08-12 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Railroad-Indians,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southern Pacific Agrees to Pay $1.2 Million in Indian Land Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A railroad company will pay an Indian tribe
$1.2 million to end a century-old dispute over reservation land
acquired in the 1860s when the industry steamed its way West.
   ``As far as the railroad is concerned, we've settled with the
Indians and we're out of it,'' Nathan Jenkins, an attorney for the
Southern Pacific Transportation Co., said Friday. ``How the money
is distributed is up to the government and the tribe.
   Representatives for the Walker River Paiute tribe could not be
reached by telephone for comment on the trespassing case.
   U.S. District Court Judge Howard McKibben on Wednesday signed an
order approving the $1.2 million settlement, which will be held by
the court until officials decide how to distribute the money.
   Jenkins said the class-action lawsuit potentially involves from
300 to 500 Walker River Paiutes who could get a share of the
settlement.
   The tribe initially sought as much as $16 million, while the
railroad said the disputed land was worth only about $750 when
Southern Pacific acquired it. The railroad at first offered a
$30,000 settlement in the case.
   The dispute involves about 400 acres in west-central Nevada from
Wabuska in Lyon County to near the northern end of the Walker River
in Mineral County.
   The tribe filed suit in 1972 because the railroad never
officially gained congressional approval for a right of way through
the Walker River Indian Reservation to lay out its tracks.
   The Indians said that as a result, Southern Pacific was
trespassing and the tribe should be compensated for the use of the
land that rightfully should belong to the Paiutes.
   The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco agreed with
the Indians that the railroad failed to comply with several federal
acts governing tribal lands. The appeals court last year remanded
the case to the district level to award trespassing damages to the
tribe.
   More than 100 year ago, the Indians agreed to take $750 for the
land along with the promise from Southern Pacific for free rides to
Indians forever.
   The railroad agreed, but never built passenger cars for the
trains that ran on the line, which carried mostly explosives for
area military operations and other goods.
   As a result, Indians were forced to ride in boxcars or cattle
cars or on top of the trains, sometimes falling off, according to
old newspaper clippings.
   ``Members of the tribe were basically treated like cattle,''
says Edgar Cook, Kansas City, Mo., economist who studied the
history of the line for the U.S. Justice Department.
</TEXT>
