<FIRST>r a PM-Lites Sub a0447 08-12 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites, Sub, a0447,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st item to DELETE extraneous material in 5th graf, `Sharon
Sharp ...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A custodian has been declared the winner of a $3
million Lotto jackpot even though he has no winning ticket to show
for it.
   Sixty-year-old Julius Russell Jr. claimed he lost the ticket.
Circuit Judge Robert Sklodowski believed him, and ordered the
Illinois State Lottery to make him a millionaire.
   ``Russell provided evidence that he consistantly played the same
two sets of numbers on a weekly basis, and the lottery verified
that the winning ticket was purchased at the store where Russell
said he always bought his tickets,'' said Sklodowski in making the
ruling Thursday.
   Guy Lahr, an attorney for the lottery, said the 60-year-old
Russell did show officials other tickets with the winning numbers,
but all are dated after the Nov. 9, 1985, drawing, Lahr said.
   Sharon Sharp, lottery director, said the state hasn't decided
whether to appeal the ruling.
   The lottery no longer has the $3 million, which has been turned
over to the state. If the ruling stands, the lottery may have to
ask for a special appropriation, Ms. Sharp said.
   Russell played the same numbers each week _ 4-14-16-29-37-41 _
said Peter Andjelkovich, Russell's attorney.
   Andjelkovich said Russell didn't find out he had won until a
year after the drawing, when Russell's daughter, Julie, recognized
the winning number in a newspaper article that said no one had yet
claimed the $3 million Lotto prize.
   ``Russell screamed `Oh my God!' and started digging through his
lottery tickets,'' Andjelkovich said. ``But he couldn't find it.''
   Russell and 22 other people filed claims with the lottery for
the prize.
   All were rejected because none had the actual ticket, Ms. Sharp
said.
</TEXT>
