<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeDeaths     08-12 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Deaths,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searchers Find Missing Woman, Bodies of Two Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers continued to look for a
5-year-old girl who police suspect was one of three children thrown
off a bridge by their mother.
   The mother, Regina Moss Monroe, was found Friday evening near
the edge of the Tombigbee River about half a mile from the bridge,
authorities said.
   ``She was sitting down in the water,'' Lt. Charles Burge said
Friday.
   The bodies of two of the children, James Jr., 3, and his sister,
Jessica, who would have turned 4 next week, were pulled from the
river earlier Friday.
   Burge said Mrs. Monroe has not been charged but is considered a
suspect in the children's deaths. He said Mrs. Monroe, who was
bruised and cut, was taken to Riverside Medical Center for
treatment. Police suspect she jumped into the river after throwing
the children off the bridge.
   Officials at the hospital declined to release her condition.
   Mrs. Monroe was found by searchers Friday sitting in shallow
water near the riverbank about half a mile from the Joe
McCorquodale Bridge where her car, its motor still running and
front doors open, was found Thursday night.
   The bodies of James Jr. and Jessica were sent to the state
forensics lab in Mobile for autopsies. Their sister, Alicia, is
still missing.
   Mrs. Monroe's husband, James Monroe Sr., had alerted police
after he came out of a store in the southern Alabama community at
about 11 p.m. Thursday and found the car with his wife and three
children gone.
   Monroe flagged down a passing police car and told the officer
that his wife had apparently driven off with their children, Burge
said. Monroe, 31, told police that his wife had been a patient in a
mental hospital, Burge said.
   The car was found on the bridge about an hour later.
</TEXT>
