<FIRST>r a PM-China-Interpreter     08-12 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Interpreter,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Interpreter Says She Wants to Go Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The interpreter for a Chinese acrobatic troupe
told federal immigration officials that she does not want political
asylum, and she says she wants to go home.
   Interpreter He Lanrong, 42, left the Nanjing Acrobatic Troupe on
Monday in Brooklyn. A day earlier, four of its performers had
disappeared after the troupe finished a 16-week tour with the Big
Apple Circus in Shelburne, Vt. Their whereabouts still are unknown.
   Mrs. He ``was referred to us by the United States Park Police
and we interviewed her to determine if she wanted to apply for any
benefits,'' said Charles Troy, spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service on Friday. ``She did not. She retained
counsel to advise her and that's it. She has no business before the
INS at this time.''
   Mrs. He told The New York Times that she left the troupe because
its director had blamed her for the acrobats' disappearance and
indicated that could create problems for her husband and daughter
in China.
   ``Contrary to some news reports, I have never said that I wanted
asylum in the United States,'' the Times quoted her as saying
Friday. ``I miss my family very much, and I love my country and
wish to return.''
   Troy said he did not know if Mrs. He has left the United States.
</TEXT>
