<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0521EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strike     08-12 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strike,0544</SECOND>
<UNK>Justice Minister Warns Estonian Voting Law Illegal</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet justice minister said Estonia's effort
to tighten voting residency laws that have sparked a strike by
thousands of Russian workers is unconstitutional.
   A nationwide newspaper placed the number of strikers in the
small Baltic republic at about 40,000, more than twice as many as
local journalists and the official Tass news agency estimated.
   Veniamin Yakovlev, Soviet justice minister, Friday told the
evening television news program ``Vremya'' that Estonia ought to
reconsider the law, which sets residence requirements to protect
Estonians' hold on the republic.
   ``I think it's obvious that this Estonian law doesn't correspond
to our constitution,'' Yakovlev said. ``This means that a
significant portion of the population will be left out.''
   Yakovlev said the law, passed Tuesday, also violated
international conventions on civil rights that the Soviet Union has
signed.
   But instead of flatly declaring the law void, Yakovlev appealed
to the Estonian Supreme Soviet to reconsider it.
   Under the law, residents of Estonia cannot vote unless they have
lived in the same district for at least two years, or have lived
anywhere in the republic for a total of five years.
   Candidates for elective office must live in the same place for
five years, or in Estonia for 10 years.
   Russian-speaking workers walked off their jobs the day after the
law was passed, and sent a delegation to Moscow to seek meetings
with national officials. Vasily Makismov, a member of the strike
committee, said in an interview from Tallinn that one member of the
delegation had returned and was meeting with strikers this morning.
   Maksimov said railroad stations were on strike and that the
state-run Aeroflot airline was shipping only emergency items such
as medical supplies and equipment. Passenger service was not
affected.
   The newspaper Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya reported today that
more than 30 factories and other state-run businesses were on
strike, including about 40,000 workers.
   ``Dialogue between the leaders of the republic and the strikers
has practically come to a halt,'' it said.
   The Estonian leadership acknowledged in a statement released
Friday that it failed to ``take into account fully the growth of
national consciousness among the non-Estonian population of the
republic,'' Tass reported.
   The Estonian parliament banned strikes Thursday, but the
strikers ignored the action.
   Tass on Friday put the number of strikers in Tallinn at 16,000.
A few enterprises in Kokhla-Jarve, a mining town east of Tallinn,
also were reported to be on strike.
   Strike committee members said workers at 42 Estonian factories
and firms walked out, but local journalists said they counted only
about 24 Estonian enterprises with striking employees.
   Non-Estonian residents of the republic, including leaders of the
Russian-dominated InterMovement group, complain the law is aimed at
them because many are new arrivals.
   They are also upset by a law making Estonian the official
language.
   Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the
population. Russians make up about a third of the 1.6 million
people.
   Sotsialisticheskaya Industriya quoted striking workers as
complaining that they want to get into courses to learn Estonian,
but that the few available are crowded and expensive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
