<DOCNO> AP890812-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0545EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Ethiopia-Leland 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Leland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0440,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Intensified With Four Helicopters, Distress Signal Site Rechecked</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with four U.S. helicopters joining search, one
distress signal area rechecked, rough weather, ADDS background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four U.S. Blackhawk helicopters
joined an aerial search today for Rep. Mickey Leland and 15 others
missing since their plane left for a southwestern refugee camp five
days ago.
   Also today, Ethiopian helicopters rechecked one of two areas
outside the plane's flight path where a satellite picked up an
apparent distress signal, said James Haley, U.S. Embassy spokesman
in the capital.
   The UH-60 Blackhawk helicopters arrived Friday from Eglin Air
Force Base in Florida and joined two U.S. C-130 Hercules cargo
planes in the search of the rugged mountains southwest of the
capital, Haley said.
   ``They are capable of staying in the air all day because the
C-130s have refueling capability,'' Haley said.
   He said search efforts by the C-130s was concentrated on the
intended flight path of the twin-engine plane that disappeared
Monday with Leland on board. The Texas Democrat, chairman of the
House Select Committee on Hunger, was accompanied by eight other
Americans.
   The Twin Otter aircraft, owned by Ethiopia's government relief
agency, was en route from Addis Ababa to the Fugnido refugee camp
450 miles away near the Sudanese border.
   The C-130s joined the search Thursday when they arrived from
West Germany.
   Haley said today that the weather ``was not cooperating, but
they are able to search.''
   Weather has hampered the search since it began Tuesday and may
have played a role in the disappearance of the Canadian-made plane,
which seats up to 20 passengers. Officials have said the plane's
takeoff Monday morning was delayed two hours by rough weather and
that it departed in heavy clouds and poor visibility.
   The site of the apparent distress signal being checked again is
in an area around Goba about 85 miles southeast of the capital,
Haley said.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration in
Washington has said its weather satellites picked up signals in
that area as well as about 100 miles north of Addis Ababa. A land
and air search of both areas on Friday turned up nothing.
   Asked how the satellites could have recorded false signals,
Haley replied, ``I've been trying to get an answer to that myself.''
   Leland's plane was equipped with an emergency locator
transmittor, a device usually mouted in the tail of an aircraft and
activated either automatically by impact or manually by the pilot.
   U.S. State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said in
Washington Friday the passengers had some box lunches, one or two
cases of soft drinks and 35 gallons of water. The prospect of
temperatures that can drop to freezing at night was a troubling
factor.
   Planes must fly over mountainous terrain to reach the Fugnido
refugee camp, but the route was not over the area where rebels are
battling Ethiopia's government. Ethiopia's separatist movements are
based in the northern part of the country in the Horn of Africa.
   A spokeswoman for Leland complained Friday that the rescue
effort lacked urgency.
   ``With all of the sophisticated surveillance that we have, with
all of the sophisticated equipment we have, we should have located
them by now,'' Alma Newsom said in Washington.
   President Bush, the State Department and Defense Department
defended the search efforts, which involved scores of U.S. military
personnel.
   ``I can understand the anxiety of all this and I can understand
the concern that people that love Mickey Leland feel and that I
feel,'' Bush said. ``But there's a lot going on, so let's just hope
and pray he's OK.''
   The Pentagon said late Friday that 170 military personnel had
been assigned to the search and that the number soon would reach
260.
   Air Force Maj. Gen. James F. Record, director of operations for
Central Command, was to leave today to take charge of the search,
the Pentagon said.
   The Pentagon said in a statement that two U-2 photographic
reconnaissance planes had exposed more than a mile of film in runs
over the 56,000-square mile search area, of which about 60 percent
was covered by clouds.
   Twelve Ethiopian helicopters also participated in the search.
   Haley said the eight other Americans aboard included three
members of Leland's staff, a friend of the congressman's, three
officers of the U.S. Agency for International Development officers
and the spouse of one AID official. Also aboard were an Ethiopian
employee of the U.S. Embassy, three Ethiopian officials and the
crew.
   Two of Leland's congressional colleagues, Reps. Gary Ackerman
and Alan Wheat, arrived in Addis Ababa early Friday to observe the
search effort. With them was Jack Russ, the sergeant-at-arms of the
House.
   Fugnido camp is run by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
and is one of four in the region that house more than 300,000
refugees who have fled civil war in neighboring Sudan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
