<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-12 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Falls Over East Coast; Flood Warnings Issued</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain soaked parts of the northern Atlantic Coast states early
today, prompting flash flood warnings for all of Connecticut, the
New York City area and northern New Jersey.
   Late Friday, 3 to 6 inches of rain fell in portions of central
and eastern Connecticut and in Long Island.
   Light rain continued this morning from Maine to Virginia and
eastern North Carolina.
   Near the Nevada-California state line, heavy rain fell Friday at
Bishop and Benton, Calif., and nearly 4 inches inches fell in 3
hours at Dyer, Nev. Water washed over parts of Highway 6 near the
state line.
   In Tucson, Ariz., thunderstorms caused some street flooding late
Friday.
   Nearly 2 inches of rain fell in less than an hour at Haswell,
Colo., and showers were scattered from western Nebraska to the
Colorado and Kansas lines. Thunderstorms also were active this
morning over central New Mexico.
   Heavier rain in the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT included
nearly an inch and a half at Fargo, N.D., more than an inch at
Salisbury, Md., nearly an inch at Atlantic City, N.J., and about
three-quarters of an inch at New York City.
   The high temperature for the nation on Friday was 105 degrees at
Coolidge, Ariz.
   A record low for the date was set at Savannah, Ga., which
recorded 64 degrees just before midnight.
   Today's forecast called for widespread rain across the northern
and middle Atlantic Coast states; showers and thunderstorms
scattered over the south Atlantic and Gulf Coast states, from the
Great Lakes region to the lower Ohio Valley and from western
portions of the central and southern Plains across the Rockies to
the central and southern Plateau region; and numerous showers and
thunderstorms from northwest Texas to the Colorado Rockies.
   Predicted highs: in the 80s across most of the nation; in the
upper 60s and 70s from New England to the Carolinas, over portions
of Colorado and along the Pacific Coast; in the lower 90s over
Florida, Mississippi, western sections of the northern Plains and
in the Great Basin area; in the 90s from southern Texas across much
of New Mexico and southern Arizona to interior valleys of
California, with readings over 100 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 92 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   EAST: Atlanta 67 fair; Boston 63 foggy; Buffalo 67 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 69 cloudy; Cleveland 60 fair; Detroit 65 fair;
Miami 80 partly cloudy; New York 65 rain; Philadelphia 65 rain;
Portland, Maine, 60 drizzle; Washington 67 foggy.
   CENTRAL: Bismarck 61 fair; Chicago 69 hazy; Denver 63 showery;
Des Moines 65 fair; Fort Worth 70 fair; Indianapolis 62 foggy;
Kansas City 66 fair; New Orleans 70 foggy; St. Louis 70 fair;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 68 cloudy.
   WEST: Albuquerque 72 partly cloudy; Anchorage 61 cloudy; Las
Vegas 82 fair; Los Angeles 65 fair; Salt Lake City 68 partly
cloudy; San Diego 69 fair; San Francisco 58 cloudy; Seattle 62 fair.
   CANADA: Montreal 66 cloudy; Toronto 66 cloudy.
</TEXT>
