<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0639EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Chile     08-12 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Registration of Presidential Candidates Ends in Chile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Registration of presidential candidates
closed with a Christian Democrat backed by a 17-party opposition
group pitted against an ex-Cabinet member under rightist military
President Augusto Pinochet.
   Also Friday, a government spokesman said Cabinet changes will be
announced next week. He said some ministers were expected to step
down and run for senator in the scheduled Dec. 14 general
elections, the first since a bloody 1973 coup led by Pinochet.
   Patricio Aylwin, 70, the centrist Christian Democratic Party
president, and Hernan Buchi, 40, finance minister for four years
until he resigned in April, were the principal presidential
candidates to register with the national elections board.
   A conservative businessman, Francisco Errazuriz, and an
internationally recognized child nutrition specialist, Fernando
Monckeberg, also registered but were not expected to draw
widespread support.
   Opinion polls show Aylwin, a former senate president, with a
huge lead over Buchi. Aylwin is supported by 17 centrist and
leftist parties that united last year to defeat a referendum
proposal that Pinochet remain in power until 1997.
   Buchi emerged only Thursday night as the principal
pro-government candidate when a rival, Sergio Jarpa, 68, announced
he would not run for president.
   Buchi, an independent, is backed by the Pinochet government and
a well-financed group of business leaders. They pressed Jarpa,
leader of National Renovation, not to split the pro-government camp
by opposing Buchi. National Renovation is the principal rightist
party.
   Pinochet could not run because the constitution prohibits a
president from holding two consecutive terms. He has said he plans,
however, to remain commander of the country's powerful army for
eight more years. The law bars the new president from removing him
from that post.
   Registration of candidates for the House of Deputies also ended
on Friday, with more than 300 pursuing the House's 120 seats.
Registration of candidates for the 38 Senate seats ends Sept. 7.
   Pinochet, 73, seized power on Sept. 11, 1973, toppling an
elected leftist government during a period of social and economic
disorder. He was obliged to call elections when voters last October
rejected a proposal that he remain the nation's leader until 1997.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
