<FIRST>r p PM-TexasElection     08-12 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Election,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Voters To Decide Replacement for Wright</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fort Worth-area voters cast ballots today in a
special election to select a replacement for former U.S. House
Speaker Jim Wright.
   Four Democrats, three Republicans and a Libertarian are on the
ballot to fill the District 12 seat Wright first was elected to in
1955.
   Wright stepped down as speaker in May and later resigned his
House seat in the face of an ethics investigation that turned up 69
instances of alleged rules violations.
   Wright, a Democrat, has not endorsed anyone.
   The Democrats vying for his spot are Pete Geren, Jim Lane and
George Petrovich Jr., all Fort Worth attorneys, and Bill Turner,
who owns a fence store.
   Laraine Bethke, a former aide to U.S. Rep. Dick Armey, Jim
Hunter, a private investigator, and Dr. Bob Lanier, a physician
with a syndicated televison show on health matters, are the
Republican candidates. Robert Buckingham Jr., manager of an
oil-change garage, is the Libertarian.
   The special election is to fill the rest of Wright's term,
ending in January 1991. A runoff is expected in late August or
September because no candidate is expected to win 50 percent of the
vote.
   Lanier, who is host of the nationally syndicated television show
``60 Second Housecall,'' and Geren are considered the front-runners.
   The two were leaders in a recent poll and each has his party's
endorsement, although Lane has important endorsements from labor
and police.
</TEXT>
