<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Grouse     08-12 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Grouse,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animal Activists Disrupt Start of Grouse Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal rights campaigners crept onto moors before
dawn in northern England today to disrupt an already quiet Glorious
Twelfth of August, the traditional opening of the grouse season.
   About 90 supporters of the Hunt Saboteurs' Association occupied
two northern English moors in Geltsdale, near Carlisle and Stanhope
to shoo away the birds, said a spokesman, Ben Ponton.
   ``The action will go on as long as it has to,'' he said. ``The
shooting parties are driving around but have made no attempt to get
onto the moors.''
   Another 100 members had also gathered in Bowland but thick mist
had kept hunters away, said Ponton, whose group annually tries to
disrupt the shooting of the prized game.
   Aristocrats and wealthy tourists organize hunting parties on
Scottish and English moors to kick off the Glorious Twelfth, and in
past years restaurants have vied to bring the birds to the table.
   But this year disease has decimated the flocks, leading to the
cancellation of many shoots.
   ``Grouse numbers are 20 percent down in some parts of Scotland
and there's no shooting at all today in parts of the north of
England'' where populations have fallen 50 percent, said Dr. Peter
Hudson of the private research group the Game Conservancy.
   Influenced by the animal protesters of recent years and worries
over declining numbers of the birds, hotels and restaurants have
all but dropped their own colorful races to serve the birds.
   The prestigious Gleneagles Hotel, once a forerunner in the
competition, said it will donate the money it would have used for
the race to grouse preservation research for a fifth year.
   But the bird will still feature on the menu of some restaurants,
served with thin fried potatoes, parsley and a bread sauce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
