<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil-Kidnap     08-12 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Kidnap,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Surround Kidnappers, Agree To Swap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interstate chase that turned
into a standoff between police and kidnappers armed with grenades
and holding three hostages stretched into a fourth day today on a
south-central highway, officials said.
   The kidnappers, identified as two married couples who earlier
obtained a $42,000 ransom in exchange for freeing a 9-year-old boy
they abducted, set a 3 p.m. (2 p.m. EDT) deadline to swap their
captives for food, a pilot and a getaway helicopter to fly them to
Paraguay.
   ``The trade will be made at that time without any tricks,''
police Officer Nivaldo de Pirondi said in a telephone interview
from Presidente Prudente, near the site of the standoff and 525
miles west of Rio.
   ``We don't want to do anything to provoke the kidnappers and put
the hostages' lives at risk,'' de Pirondi said. ``We are dealing
with professionals, but they are charged up and could do something
irrational at any moment.''
   He said the hostages _ two TV reporters and the driver of the
armored car _ were in fair physical condition. They were being held
in the armored car, which about 100 heavily armed police have
surrounded since early Friday with sharpshooters aiming at the
car's small windows.
   The standoff began after a three-day chase through south-central
Brazil, police said.
   Authorities were delayed in meeting the kidnappers' demands
because the first aircraft developed mechanical trouble and was
grounded in a nearby field, de Pirondi said.
   He said a second helicopter was summoned from Brasilia, the
capital, and was due to arrive early this afternoon.
   The drama began Aug. 3, when the two couples abducted 9-year-old
Said Agel Filho from his home in the central Brazilian city of
Goiania, 565 miles northwest of Sao Paulo. The kidnapping was kept
secret at first to protect the child, police said.
   Six days later, police found where the boy was being held, but
the kidnappers negotiated a ransom of about $42,000 and an armored
car for their getaway. They then took the two TV reporters and
headed for the Goiania Airport.
   However, Goias state authorities failed to provide an airplane
and pilot for their escape, and the kidnappers set off on an
interstate flight through the states of Goias, Minas Gerais and Sao
Paulo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
