<DOCNO> AP890812-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0904EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     08-12 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamils: More Than 50 Civilians Killed in Indian Army Offensive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian troops killed at least 51
civilians after being attacked by Tamil rebels in a northern town,
Tamil sources said today.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 40 houses
and 23 shops were set on fire by the soldiers after an army patrol
was ambushed Aug. 2 in the town of Velvettiturai, 200 miles north
of Colombo. At least six soldiers were killed in the attack,
military officials said at the time.
   The Tamil sources, who have proved reliable in the past, quoted
residents as saying the Indian peacekeeping troops imposed a
48-hour curfew on Velvettiturai after the ambush and carried out
search operations.
   Many houses were shelled and several people were burned to
death, the sources said. They said that 51 victims were identified
by relatives after the curfew was withdrawn.
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the rebel group fighting
the Indians, said in a statement telexed to newspaper offices that
at least 70 civilians were killed in the offensive. The Tigers'
accounts of casualties have proved to be exaggerated in the past.
   Sri Lankan military officials confirmed a major operation by
Indian troops occurred in Velvettiturai, but they said they did not
have details because they do not operate in the Tamil-dominated
areas of the country.
   In New Delhi, a government spokesman said there were 18 civilian
casualties in an exchange of gunfire between the soldiers and the
rebels after the ambush.
   He said the rebels used civilians as cover while firing with
rocket-propelled grenades and automatic rifles at the Indian army
patrol.
   ``The troops returned fire and 30 bodies were recovered after
the fighting,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules. ``At least five were hard-core Tigers and seven
others were sympathizers.''
   ``Eighteen unfortunate civilians were killed in the cross
fire,'' he said. The spokesman denied that civilians were killed
during the curfew.
   ``The Tamils in Velvettiturai will say whatever the Tigers tell
them to,'' he said. ``The Tigers' capacity to kill fellow Tamils is
unlimited and they live in fear of retribution.''
   Indian soldiers have been in Sri Lanka's Tamil-dominated north
and east for the past two years to put down the Tamil war for an
independent homeand.
   They were deployed to supervise an India-sponsored accord under
which Sri Lanka offered Tamils limited autonomy in exchange for an
arms surrender. But the Tigers rejected the agreement and turned
their guns on the Indians.
   India got involved because of the sympathies of its own 60
million Tamils to the rebel cause.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
allege they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up
75 percent of the population and control the government and the
military.
   Militant Tamils launched their separatist war in 1983. At least
11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have been killed in
the fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
