<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 0915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0468 08-12 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0468,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian, Christian Gunners Locked in Fierce Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE casualties and ADD French appeal. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners locked in
one of their fiercest battles in months pummeled the Beirut area
today in an exchange that reportedly left at least 12 people dead
and 48 wounded.
   Smoke from shells and fires in nearby hills hung like a funeral
shroud over the city. Five months of such duels have prompted all
but about 200,000 of Beirut's 1.5 million residents to flee.
   Police said at least 12 people were killed and 48 wounded in
today's fighting between Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000 predominantly
Christian troops and 40,000 Syrian soldiers and their Moslem
militia allies.
   More than 40 have died in the past two days, bringing the toll
since March 8 to 598 killed and 1,562 wounded, according to
security sources.
   Radios interrupted their programs with bulletins about where
shells were falling and to report fires blazing out of control in
several parts of Beirut.
   A police spokesman said fierce clashes with machine guns,
recoilless cannons and rocket-propelled grenade launchers raged
across Beirut's dividing Green Line and the eastern flank of the
Christian enclave.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem cabinet
vying for power with the military cabinet under Aoun, said: ``We're
left in the blowing wind with no roof above us.''
   ``The problem in Lebanon is that our wise people are not active
and our active people are not wise,'' Hoss said in a statement
broadcast by Voice of the Nation radio.
   The French and Argentine embassies in neighboring Baabda were
hit by Syrian rockets and one French embassy guard was slightly
wounded, security sources said. The embassies are only a hundred
yards away from the shell-shattered presidential palace, where Aoun
has been living in a bunker since the latest round of fighting in
Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war began in March.
   The security sources said the residences of U.S. Ambassador John
McCarthy and French Ambassador Rene Ala in suburban Yarze east of
Beirut came under shellfire for a second night in a row, but no
casualties or serious damage were reported.
   In Paris, the French Foreign Ministry said today that it had
asked Syrian officials in Damascus to immediately end the Syrian
bombardments. The ministry also called for all sides to lift
blockades and begin peace talks.
   In Washington Friday, State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler called for all parties to cease fire, but she also singled
out Syria for its use of heavy weapons against civilians.
   ``The United States condemns the indiscriminate slaughter of
innocent people and the renewed use of heavy caliber weapons, such
as the 240-millimeter mortar, which are in the Syrian arsenal,''
Ms. Tutwiler said.
   ``We again call upon Syria, an active participant in the
fighting, the Lebanese armed forces, as well as the various
Lebanese factions, for an immediate cease-fire.''
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing
regulations, said Syrian gunners opened fire at 6 a.m. from
multibarreled rocket launchers at the Christian enclave, shattering
a two-hour lull in the fighting.
   The whooshing sound of outgoing rockets echoed across the
mountains southeast of Beirut. A few minutes later, howitzer shells
fired by Aoun's gunners crashed into the region, sending palls of
dust and smoke into the sky.
   Syrian soldiers deserted their sand-bagged checkpoints at the
Khaldeh junction south of Beirut and sought refuge in fox holes
along the sandy coast.
   Several motorists abandoned their cars and fled under the main
highway bridge in Khaldeh. Others sped away.
   Aoun's gunners, using 155-mm U.S.-made howitzers, concentrated
their shelling on Syrian artillery emplacements, truck-mounted
rocket launchers and communications posts in the hills of Aramoun
and Doha, above Khaldeh.
   A howitzer shell, fired by Aoun's gunners, scored a direct hit
on a 40-barrel rocket launcher on a hilltop in Aramoun, setting it
on fire.
   Black smoke billowed from the truck-mounted launcher for 20
minutes, during which the Syrians intensified their shelling of the
Christian enclave, operating more than a dozen rocket launchers in
unison.
   Security sources said rockets and shells fired by Syrian gunners
targeted almost every town and village in the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave northeast of the capital.
</TEXT>
