<FIRST>r i PM-PLO-Israel     08-12 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO-Israel,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatah Congress Reaffirms Right to Armed Struggle Against Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fifth congress of Fatah, the largest
arm of the PLO, has issued a final declaration rejecting terrorism
but reaffirming the right to armed struggle against Israeli
occupation.
   The declaration, made public late Friday night, said the
congress has decided to mobilize ``all means'' to assure
continuation of the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   It also called on the United States to ``clearly recognize'' the
right of Palestinians to self-determination and an independent
state.
   The eight-day congress of more than 1,000 delegates of the
mainstream branch of the Palestine Liberation Organization ended
Thursday. It had called on Tuesday for ``intensification of the
armed struggle and all other forms of battle to put an end to the
Israeli occupation of Palestinian territories.''
   The final declaration reiterated the call to intensify the
uprising, mobilizing ``all means'' available. It also called for
the reinforcement of the uprising's unified command and developing
a role for people's committees.
   The congress reiterated Fatah's rejections of ``all forms of
terrorism, notably state terrorism.'' But it reaffirmed its ``right
to use all means, including armed struggle, to confront the Israeli
occupier, in conformity with United Nations declarations on the
rights of the Palestinian people.''
   The final statement deplored the slow pace of the U.S.-PLO
dialogue, which got under way Dec. 16. It called on the Americans
to ``clearly recongize the right of Palestinians to
self-determination and the establishment of an independent state
having Jerusalem as its capital, and to depart from their
partiality vis-a-vis Israel.''
   The United States opened a formal dialogue with the PLO after
the organization's leader, Yasser Arafat, renounced terrorism and
implicitly recognized Israel's right to exist.
</TEXT>
