<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-US     08-12 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Group Suspects U.S. Involvement With Philippine Vigilantes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Roman Catholic priests and
nuns announced today it has asked national lawmakers to investigate
whether the United States has promoted anti-Communist vigilantes in
this country.
   The Philippine military has used vigilante groups as support
units to combat a 20-year-old communist insurgency. Some members
belong to religious cults, and some have been criticized for
violating human rights during sweeps of suspected rebel hideouts.
   In its statement distributed to news agencies today, The
Association of Major Religious Superiors in the Philippines said it
had asked the country's two-chamber Congress ``to initiate a
comprehensive investigation into and expose the extent of reported
U.S. involvement, both directly and indirectly, in supporting the
formation, training and operation of vigilante groups.''
   It said, ``The nation is caught in a vicious war and is
experiencing an escalation of violence. This phenomenon is not
unconnected with an international organized effort to polarize the
situation along ideological lines.'' The statement gave no
specifics of purported U.S. involvement with vigilante groups.
   The Catholic group, which includes at least 10,000 priests and
nuns, also requested the investigation during its national
convention late last month.
