<FIRST>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0435 08-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0435,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronauts Near End of Secret Space Shuttle Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th and 5th grafs, `The National...', with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with landing time announced, quote. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The weather...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia's astronauts closed down
experiments and checked flight control systems today as they
prepared to end their secret military mission on Sunday with a
landing in the California desert.
   Commander Brewster Shaw and pilot Richard Richards were to run
through a series of tests to make certain the shuttle's computers
and control jets were ready for the return to Earth.
   Mission specialists David Leestma, James Adamson and Mark Brown
were to pack up the experiments, some of which were believed to be
connected with the ``Star Wars'' spaceborne missile defense
project. Others tested the astronauts' capabilities as military
observers in space.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration broke the
official silence on the mission today to announce that Columbia
would land at 9:37 a.m. EDT Sunday in the Mojave Desert at Edwards
Air Force, Calif., after a flight of five days, one hour. Earlier,
it had said only that landing would take place between 9 a.m. and
noon.
   ``The crew is doing well and is beginning landing
preparations,'' a statement said.
   The weather forecast called for excellent landing conditions at
Edwards on Sunday, with partly cloudy skies and temperatures
expected from 68 just after sunrise to a midday high of 97 degrees.
   The Air Force base, which has been host to as many as half a
million people for shuttle landings, will be closed to the public
Sunday because of the military nature of the flight.
   The news blackout was imposed by the Defense Department, which
wants to keep the flight's goals a secret. But Air Force Secretary
Donald Rice reported Wednesday that a satellite was deployed by the
astronauts during their first day in orbit on Tuesday.
   Rice was mum about the satellite's purpose, but it is widely
believed to be a 10-ton spy satellite designed to take very
detailed photographs of military targets over a wide area of the
globe, including most of the Soviet Union. It would help the United
States verify Soviet compliance with arms agreements.
   The crew of five military officers also reportedly monitored
military tactical and strategic targets on Earth.
</TEXT>
