<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru a0464 08-12 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0464,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Rally, Urge Strikers to `Hang In There'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with morning rally. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `The AFL-CIO...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' striking unions today launched a
large new lobbying effort after a week when hundreds of their own
pilots and flight attendants crossed picket lines.
   ``Now they're out there telling the world it's over. Well, it's
not over,'' Charles E. Bryan, leader of Eastern's Machinists union,
exhorted some 300 people at a morning rally across the street from
Eastern corporate headquarters. ``So hang in there. There'll be
good news coming.''
   Bryan joined Henry A. Duffy, national president of the Air Line
Pilots Association, and other leaders on the first blocks of a
``moving picket line'' march that began a 26-day, 13-state series
of parades, motorcades, rallies and lobbying efforts.
   ``Before this is over, the whole country's going to wake up to
what's going on,'' said John J. Bavis, chairman of the Eastern
pilots union local.
   The AFL-CIO, Machinists and flight attendants are also
participating in the rallies, but the strike's sixth month has
begun with a wave of picket-line defections, prompting Eastern to
say Friday it no longer needed to hire pilots.
   Eastern, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization
five days after being hit by a crippling strike by its three unions
March 4, plans to rebuild to an airline two-thirds its pre-strike
size. The company's plan for its creditors said it would be flying
800 daily flights with 1,700 pilots by the end of the year.
   Eastern has 350 daily flights, compared to nearly 1,100 before
the strike.
   Company spokesman Robin Matell declined to give figures on
Eastern's pilots, but sources speaking on condition of anonymity
have said more than 600 union pilots are flying, including some 250
who have crossed picket lines since the union leadership last
weekend discussed ending the strike.
   Eastern has graduated 300 newly hired pilots from training and
has from 700 to 800 in training.
   Veteran pilots who want to return to work now will instead be
put on ``a preferential recall list'' and given priority for future
openings, Matell said.
   Hank Weber, spokesman for Eastern's Air Line Pilots Association,
was skeptical about whether Eastern has hired enough qualified
pilots, but said Friday's announcement will stop the flow of pilot
crossovers.
   ``There were people who crossed the picket line because of
uncertainty,'' Weber said. ``That will stop now. Thank you,
Eastern.''
   Weber said the vast majority of the 3,600 ALPA Eastern pilots
remain strongly committed to the strike.
   Meanwhile, officials said the number of flight attendants
abandoning the strike after more than five months has also jumped
this week.
   A source who spoke on the condition of not being identified said
140 flight attendants crossed the picket lines this week, probably
because of perceptions that the pilot crossovers hurt the strike.
   ``I'm not really sure on the complete impact,'' said Mary Jane
Barry, president of the flight attendants union. ``When there's a
breaking in the ranks, it affects all of us.''
   She said she didn't have any figures on total flight attendant
crossovers, but did not dispute a figure of at least 1,000 from the
union's 6,000 members.
   Eastern's rebuilding plan calls for 3,400 flight attendants.
Company officials have said 1,000 new flight attendants have been
hired or are in training. Eastern has received 31,000 applications
and is being ``very, very selective,'' Matell said.
   The 8,500-member Machinists union, joined by the other two
unions when it struck March 4 after 1{ years of federal mediation
failed, has held relatively solid. Some 100 union mechanics are
working for Eastern, which also has hired several hundred more and
is using 700 supervisors in maintenance roles.
   Eastern wants 2,500 mechanics by year's end, the company has
said.
</TEXT>
