<FIRST>u s PM-GLF--PGAGeneral 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GLF--PGA General, 1st Ld-Writethru,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with completion of second round</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE MOOSHIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAWTHORN WOODS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike ``Radar'' Reid, a short hitter
playing on a long course, took a two-stroke lead today into the
third round of the 71st PGA championship.
   Reid shot 34-33_67 in Friday's rain-delayed round to go with his
opening round of 66 for an 11-under-par 133.
   Trailing Reid were Leonard Thompson, who shared the first-round
lead with Reid, and Craig Stadler at 135.
   Tom Watson, another stroke back at 136, was seeking the only
major championship he has not won in his quest for a rare career
grand slam of the major tournaments.
   Stadler shot a course record 33-31_64 in a bogey-free second
round for his 135.
   Jack Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer made the cut of one-over-par 145
for the top 70 scorers. Nicklaus had a four-under 140 and Palmer,
who electrified the crowds Thursday with a 68, had a second-round
74 for 142.
   Grouped at 137 were Dave Rummells, Chris Perry, Ed Fiori and
Andy Bean. U. S. Open champion Curtis Strange was at 138. Defending
champion Jeff Sluman and pre-tournament favorite Greg Norman barely
made the cut at 145.
   Failing to make the cut were former PGA champions Lee Trevino,
Lanny Wadkins, John Mahaffey, David Graham, Hal Sutton and Bob
Tway. Other casualties included former U.S. Open and Masters champ
Fuzzy Zoeller, Mark O'Meara and Scott Verplank.
   Because of the rain delay Friday, the last eight groups of 24
golfers finished the second round early this morning.
   Reid, who earned his nickname because of his exact shot-making
ability, agreed that he was an unlikely leader.
   ``But that's the great thing about sports,'' he said. ``The
(Chicago) Cubs shouldn't be in first place in August, either.''
   Watson, 39, stayed close while the other heroes of decades past,
Jack Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer, fell back.
   ``If you'd asked me two months ago if I had a chance to win the
PGA, I'd have said `no,''' Watson said Friday. ``The leader board
says `yes.'''
   It says no to Palmer, 59, and Nicklaus, 49, despite their
impressive early play.
   Nicklaus called his round ``another adventure. I had only one
easy par. I was all over the course. If it hadn't been for my
putter, I'd be in the 80s.''
   He hasn't been using his driver because of his erratic play with
it.
   ``I'm going to use my driver if I can,'' he said. ``If I hit it,
it will give me a chance to get home in two. I need it on a few
holes.''
   Does that mean Nicklaus still thinks he can win his sixth PGA
title?
   ``I'm in good shape. When you're four under in the PGA, I don't
care who's leading, I know I'm not going to be very far off.''
   Palmer made the turn at five under, but dropped a shot at No. 11
with a bogey-5.
   ``Three-putting No. 11 threw me off track,'' said Palmer, whose
Army was marching again after his exciting opening round.
   He missed a five-foot putt for a birdie at No. 12 and took a
double bogey-5 at the 13th.
   ``Other than that, I had a solid round,'' Palmer said. ``I
didn't feel any letdown, I just had to work hard to keep it
together.''
   Palmer parred the last five holes and said, ``I still feel good
and I feel good about the way I'm hitting the ball.''
   It marked the first time Palmer has made the cut in a major
tournament since the 1987 PGA. He made the cut in all four majors
in 1983.
   Play was suspended Friday for one hour, 48 minutes in the
afternoon because of a rainstorm.
   Once again, the 7,197-yard Kemper Lakes layout had ideal playing
conditions despite the rain delay, and the game's greatest players
took advantage.
   Reid, who missed only one green and one fairway Thursday, missed
five fairways and four greens in the second round.
   ``It wasn't as pretty,'' Reid said, ``but I showed some
character. I hung in there and got the most out of my round.''
   Stadler called his round ``very enjoyable. I made all the three,
four, five-foot putts I had. I didn't miss a fairway yesterday and
I missed only two or three today. I was happy with a solid round to
get back in the tournament.''
   Thompson also didn't play as well as he did in the first round.
   ``The first part of my round today was an adventure until I
settled down,'' said Thompson, who had an eagle, four birdies and
three bogeys.
   Strange said he would like to see the wind come up because
``Kemper Lakes is playing too easy. It is a tougher course than it
is playing.''
</TEXT>
