<FIRST>u a PM-ShuttleLanding 1stLd-Writethru a0428 08-12 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Landing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0428,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reason For Shuttle Landing Secrecy? Well, It's Sort Of Secret</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Officials declined...', to add time of landing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The desert site where up
to 500,000 people have cheered past space shuttle landings will be
empty when Columbia returns to Earth, closed by the Air Force for
unexplained security reasons.
   The Department of Defense said the secrecy was necessary to ``to
limit an adversary's ability to determine the mission of a given
DOD shuttle flight.''
   Air Force Secretary Donald Rice said Wednesday that Columbia's
crew deployed an important satellite. He declined to elaborate, but
sources close to the project have said the 10-ton satellite is
designed to snap highly-detailed photographs of military targets
over a large area of the globe, including most of the Soviet Union.
   Officials declined to elaborate on how national security might
be harmed by opening the public viewing site for Columbia's
landing, scheduled for 9:37 EDT Sunday.
   ``I really don't know,'' said Don Haley, a civilian spokesman
for the Air Force at this Mojave Desert military base.
   The site is located 3{ miles from where the shuttle rolls to a
stop on dry lakebed runway 17. It drew 500,000 spectators when
Columbia was greeted by then-President and Mrs. Reagan on July 4,
1982. It has been closed during classified military shuttle
missions.
   While the public is barred, reporters, photographers and
television camera operators will be allowed to watch and record
Columbia's landing from a media site about 2 miles from the
shuttle's stopping point.
   ``It's crazy. The Air Force likes to play I've-got-a-secret. It
makes them feel more important,'' said John Pike, space policy
analyst for the Federation of American Scientists.
   Pike said during a telephone interview from Washington that he
understands Columbia's payload was a modified version of the KH-12
photoreconnaissance satellite.
   Secrecy surrounding the shuttle ``is not protecting this mission
from the Russians. It's protecting this mission from the American
taxpayers,'' he said.
   Capt. Marty Hauser, a Pentagon spokesman, disagreed.
   Hauser said Pentagon officials ``feel we do a good job of
keeping the public informed through the media and Congress. ... We
have a very effective way of reporting on the programs we have to
the House and Senate select intelligence committees.''
</TEXT>
