<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica Bjt   08-12 0952</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, Bjt,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hopes Raised In Central America With Summit Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The agreement by Central
American presidents to disband U.S.-supported Nicaraguan rebels has
raised hopes and added momentum to the quest for peace in the
region after a decade of conflict.
   ``We Central American presidents have taken the destiny of
Central America in our own hands,'' said Costa Rican President
Oscar Arias after the accords were signed Aug. 7 in the Honduran
port of Tela.
   The presidents of Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador
and Guatemala have committed themselves to disband the 11,000
Contra rebels camped in Honduras near the Nicaraguan border by
early December.
   The deal was sealed after the others apparently concluded
Nicaragua's President Daniel Ortega was genuinely moving towards a
fair election, as he had promised so many times in the past.
   Although Central American deadlines have not often been honored,
the end of the eight-year-old Nicaraguan war seems to be in sight.
   The presidents widened the spotlight to include El Salvador. The
outlook remains problematic, but the call for a cease-fire and
democratic guarantees has provided the best opportunity in years
for progress towards ending a conflict that began in 1980.
   The Bush administration said the Contras should not be disbanded
until after Nicaragua's presidential vote, set for Feb. 25, 1990,
in order to keep the heat on the leftist Sandinista government.
   But after eight years of fighting the U.S. position appeared
sterile. Congress has been unwilling to approve military aid that
would restore the Contras as an effective force.
   El Salvador, Honduras and Costa Rica receive hundreds of
millions of dollars in aid from the United States, but sources at
the talks said the Central Americans concluded relations would not
be hurt by a decision to disband the Contras _ something that
appeared inevitable in any case.
   Besides, Nicaragua was seen as moving towards an accommodation
with its domestic opposition. Just before the summit, Ortega
obtained an agreement in which the opposition joined a call for the
Contras' demise in return for promises of electoral reform.
   The move made Ortega's promises of democratization more
credible, and Ortega sweetened the deal for Honduras' Jose Azcona
Hoyo by agreeing to drop a world court suit against Honduras for
abetting subversion of another government.
   Emilio Alvarez Montalvan, a conservative Nicaraguan politician,
attributed the eased tensions to the superpower thaw and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of ``perestroika,'' or economic
and political restructuring.
   Like the Contras, Ortega has had to deal with reduced support
from his allies; on Thursday, a Soviet official told Costa Rica's
Arias that the Soviet Union will ship halt arms shipments to
Nicaragua as a contributioon to the peace process.
   ``Neither side is interested in using Third World conflicts to
get at the other any more,'' Montalvan said.
   Guillermo Ungo, El Salvador's most prominent leftist politician,
noted that three presidents _ Azcona, Arias and Vinicio Cerezo of
Guatemala _ are near the ends of their terms.
   ``They wanted to go down on the record as having achieved
something concretely positive for regional peace,'' said Ungo, who
finished a poor third to President Alfredo Cristiani in El
Salvador's voting earlier this year.
   Ungo predicted Washington ``will continue trying to block
implementation of the Tela accords.'' But President Bush will face
a fight in Congress if he tries to extend even non-lethal aid to
the Contras in the face of Central American political agreements.
   The Sandinistas' popularity has been hurt by an economy that is
on its way to becoming the hemisphere's worst. The government
blames it on the war and a U.S. embargo. The opposition blames it
on rigid economic policies.
   Even so, the Sandinistas are still favored in 1990, and Ortega
has improved his odds by suspending the draft. With the Contras
fading, the political benefits outweighed the military need,
although occasional fighting continues in the countryside.
   The Sandinistas also have agreed to free certain political
prisoners, reopen a television channel for the opposition, allow
United Nations election observers and yield power immediately if
the opposition wins.
   Once the rebels are disbanded, the Tela accord calls for a
wide-ranging, unconditional amnesty. The Contra leadership has been
reported divided over whether to return to Nicaragua; some fear the
fighters themselves, largely poor agricultural workers, will not
want to lay down their arms.
   While the opposition is looking for more concessions, the
business of politics has begun to pick up steam in Nicaragua.
   The Supreme Electoral Council estimates 1.8 million Nicaraguans
will register. The opposition newspaper La Prensa expressed concern
about fraud, but added ``the Sandinistas have absolutely renounced
their `historic project,' which involved holding on to power in
order to install a dictatorship.''
   The Tela accords, in addition to demobilization of the Contras,
call for an end to the Salvadoran war and incorporation of the
rebels into the democratic process.
   Both the government and the rebels hailed the accords and see
improved chances for discussing peace, although there was no
requirement and no verification or enforcement provision, as there
is at the Nicaraguan end.
   The consensus among Salvadoran politicians is that resolution of
the ``Contra question'' in and of itself benefits El Salvador by
giving it attention previously monopolized by Nicaragua.
   Ortega agreed not to aid the rebels, but Salvadorans remain
skeptical about that.
   Although the two sides are far apart, the war has been going on
for even longer than Nicaragua's, without a decisive outcome. Mere
fatigue may be enough to push the sides into taking advantage of
the Tela opening.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Grant Mine, based in San Salvador,
covers Central America for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
