<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Blacks-Churches Bjt   08-12 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blacks-Churches, Bjt,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Returning to Traditional Churches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>EDS: SamsonCampbell is correct ^By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 10 years, Gilbert Ridley and his wife were
the only blacks in their Presbyterian church in Bucks County, Pa.
   Now Ridley drives 15 miles every Sunday to a small, all-black
church he attended years ago.
   ``When you're black, your life experience makes you want a
little different format,'' he says.
   So did the Rev. George A. Stallings Jr., a black priest who has
been suspended by the Roman Catholic Church for forming the Imani
Temple, a breakaway black congregation in Washington.
   Unlike Stallings and his followers, Ridley and other blacks
interviewed at the National Urban League's annual conference are
not breaking away from their mostly Protestant churches.
   But their sympathies are with Stallings, who was suspended by
the Washington archdiocese after he said Mass in defiance of
Cardinal James A. Hickey on July 2. Stallings says the Catholic
Church has failed its nearly 2 million black parishioners. He has
accused the church of racism.
   ``We are excited to see him have such a following, because I
want to see people go back to church,'' Ridley said in an interview.
   John E. Jacob, president of the Urban League, told reporters,
``I believe it would be in the Catholic Church's interest to
understand what Father Stallings is saying.
   ``If they see the African American community as important for
inclusion in the church, then they have to have an appeal to that
community,'' Jacob said in a news conference Wednesday as the
four-day meeting ended. ``They have to understand that they are in
competition with traditional black churches.''
   Blacks and church officials agreed that mainline Protestant
churches have avoided the Imani Temple type of schism by allowing
flexibility to local congregations.
   ``I think most Protestant churches are far ahead of the Catholic
Church in terms of ritual,'' said the Rev. Joseph E. Lowery,
president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference and
pastor of the Cascade United Methodist Church in Atlanta.
   ``Local churches are free to use the guidelines just as
guidelines,'' Lowery said. For years, he said, he has used the
hymn, ``Lift Every Voice and Sing,'' a black favorite, as the
doxology in place of the traditional ``Praise God from Whom all
Blessings Flow.''
   Leonard Benton, president of the Urban League in Oklahoma City
and a Lutheran, said concerns of blacks and minorities were a major
issue in the merger of the American Lutheran Church, the
Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches and the Lutheran
Church in America to form the Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America, effective last year.
   Alice E. Carter, director of education for the Pittsburgh Urban
League and wife of a Lutheran minister, said the Lutheran church,
with its German and Scandinavian underpinnings, ``has been ethnic
ever since it was formed.''
   But, she said, it is paying more attention to minorities ``at
least in words and in policy; if this can be implemented, that will
be fine.'' The issue, known in the church as inclusiveness and
diversity, is expected to be debated again when the church's
National Assembly meets in Chicago Aug. 23-30.
   Mim Woolbert, a spokeswoman at the church's headquarters in
Chicago, said, ``As far as worship concerns, I think that is
getting to be answered in each local congregation in a different
way, depending on the situation.''
   At the national office of the United Methodist Church in
Louisville, Ky., Marj Carpenter, director of news services, said,
``We can look back at pictures of our general assemblies even 30
years ago, and it will be all white males sitting there.'' Now the
moderator, or titular head, of the church, is a black woman, the
Rev. Joan SamsonCampbell of Philadelphia.
   Still, Ms. Carpenter said, blacks ``monitor us very closely ...
they call our hands quickly if we are not paying attention to their
concerns.''
   Dean F. Dale, a delegate from the Louisville Urban League who
described herself as a lifelong Baptist, said, ``I don't think
there is a trend to set up separate churches and that sort of thing
because I don't think that would solve anything. ``I think it's
just a matter of people coming together and talking through their
differences.''
   At the same time, she said, she could understand the frustration
that led Stallings to form the breakaway church.
   Ridley, minority affairs coordinator for Bucks County Community
College in Newtown, Pa., said he was not unhappy at the nearly
all-white church that he and his wife attended, where he had held a
number of church offices, but felt he could be more useful by
rejoining the all-black congregation. He said the pastor of the
larger church supported his decision to resign and be ``our
missionary'' to the smaller congregation.
   In his new church, he said, he is rediscovering the emotional
climate of black worship.
   ``I have contact again with the old black matriarchs,'' he said.
``They are beautiful. They are something you miss. And the kids.
They do their bit in the service. Tears come into your eyes when
you see them in their blue pants and blue skirts and white shirts.
They read the scripture, they do everything. I had gotten away from
all that.
   ``In a black church, you have to be very, very basic,'' he said.
``Black folks have to feel it, and if you don't make it so you can
feel it, you get bored, so you say, `Why go?'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
