<DOCNO> AP890812-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   08-12 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Rising for Bread, Staples in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the dusty, fly-ridden food bazaars
of Kabul, astute merchants check to see if roads are open or if
Moslem rebels have closed them before setting the price of rice,
flour and other staples.
   During the past month, the Logar Road, the main route to
transport grain and produce from Pakistan, has been closed. The
other key road to Pakistan, which runs southeast through the city
of Jalalabad, has been closed intermittently, though the government
has gotten convoys through guerrilla lines under military escort.
   For most of the 2.25 million Afghans living in this mile-high
capital and facing almost daily rocket attacks by the rebels, the
result of the road closures has been a sharp increase in prices on
the open market, especially for flour used to make the traditional
Afghan flat bread called ``nan.''
   ``People are not happy,'' said Gul Mohammad, a bearded trader
selling 7-pound sacks of flour at a market in western Kabul. ``They
are very hungry now because food is too expensive.''
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas, who are based in Pakistan, say
soaring prices are exactly what they want.
   Abdul Sera of the fundamentalist Hezb-e-islami Khalist group
said the guerrilla strategy is to put pressure on the capital and
force residents to evacuate, thus paving the way for attacks on the
city and the ouster of the Soviet-supported government of President
Najib.
   ``We want to make it so expensive that people leave Kabul,''
Sera told The Associated Press in Islamabad, Pakistan. ``They are
facing a big shortage of food.''
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of the fundamentalist
Jamiat-e-islami group, said rebel factions must develop a
coordinated plan to cut all roads around Kabul in order to conquer
the city.
   ``We must have total blockage,'' he told a Western journalist
last week in Peshawar, Pakistan.
   An average Afghan worker earns about 3,500 afghanis a month, now
worth less than $10. U.N. officials estimate prices have gone up
200 percent since Jan. 1.
   The closure of the Logar Road has made things worse: the price
of a 7-pound sack of flour in Kabul has risen from $1.72 on July 4
to $2.43 last week _ 27 percent of a typical worker's monthly
salary. Meanwhile, the cost of one nan has jumped from 1{ cents to
3.6 cents.
   U.N. sources say that in recent weeks they have seen many Kabul
residents migrating north, where there are fewer rocket attacks and
food is more plentiful and cheaper.
   ``I can say all people are facing malnutrition. All they have is
one piece of bread and tea three times a day,'' said Mohammad Shah,
a 33-year-old academic. ``I don't know how we survive .... If the
roads are blocked, we will die of hunger.''
   On a recent weekend, more than 100 trucks were lined up outside
Kabul's main silo waiting to unload grain, but it was not for
immediate consumption. The government is replenishing its grain
reserves to avoid a repetition of last winter's severe shortages.
   This grain shipment from the Soviet Union was transported down
the Salang Highway without apparent difficulty.
   Brian Stockwell of the World Food Program said the Afghan
government has reported the silo now holds about 20,000 metric tons
of grain, up from just under 8,000 metric tons two weeks ago. A
metric ton is equivalent to 2,205 pounds or 1.1 short tons.
   While the silo has a capacity of 50,000 tons, the Ministry of
Light Industry and Food has said it can stockpile only about 40,000
tons for the winter, Stockwell said.
   That amount represents less than half the estimated 90,000 to
100,000 tons needed to get Kabul through the three worst winter
months, he said.
   It isn't clear yet where the rest will come from _ possibly the
United Nations or the Soviets. Negotiations with the Soviets are
under way in Moscow and Geneva, Stockwell said.
   In the past week, the silo has been a prime target of rocket
attacks. Many missed, but on one day, a rocket shattered windows
and caused other minor damage.
   Meanwhile, Kabul's residents remain preoccupied with finding
enough to eat.
   Shah said he couldn't afford rice: a 7-pound sack now costs
$4.62, a little less than half his monthly salary of $10.25.
   The biggest worry, however, is flour.
   ``An Afghan will be hungry unless he gets three nans every
day,'' said a Western relief expert. ``This is the mainstay of the
Afghan diet.''
</TEXT>
