<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TiananmenMemories     08-12 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tiananmen Memories,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese May Succeed In Altering Memories of Tiananmen Square, Researcher
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chinese government's campaign to distort
the truth about the Tiananmen Square massacre may seem futile, but
even eyewitnesses could one day believe they recall the fabricated
history, a memory expert says.
   ``All the right psychological high-tech ingredients are in place
for the lie to become truth, reason enough for us to be pessimistic
about the future of memories of Tiananmen Square,'' said Elizabeth
Loftus.
   ``The Chinese government is not the first set of leaders to try
to rewrite history. Their attempts at mental manipulation are only
the most radical in recent times.
   ``We should not be complacent in thinking they can't succeed.
Rather, we should worry about whose memory is next,'' she said.
   Loftus, of the University of Washington in Seattle, cited
research into manipulation of eyewitness memories in an address
Friday at the annual meeting of the American Psychological
Association.
   Chinese authorities have been using memory-modifying techniques
to convince citizens that violence in the army's June 4 attack on
pro-democracy demonstrators was caused by rowdy civilian thugs, she
said.
   The tactics include repeated television images of soldiers being
attacked, she said. Workers, students, bureaucrats and party
members are exposed to twice-weekly ``seminars'' on the topic, and
make public pledges of allegiance to the party line, she said.
   ``People are particularly prone to having their memories
modified when the passage of time allows the original memory to
fade,'' Loftus said.
   ``In its weakened condition, memory, like the disease-ridden
body, becomes especially vulnerable to repeated assaults on its
very essence. We are especially susceptible if we can be induced
... to repeat the misinformation as fact.''
   The experiments in memory modification Loftus cited generally
shared a common strategy. People witnessed a crime, accident or
other incident, typically on film. Sometime later, they were tested
on their recall of the event.
   But some of the people were slipped fictitious details without
their realizing it, and they later recalled them as memory.
   In one experiment, subjects watched a film of an accident on a
country road. Later they were asked if they had seen a barn, which
in fact did not appear in the film.
   Researchers planted that idea of a barn in the minds of some
subjects by asking, ``How fast was the white sports car going when
it passed the barn?''
   Of the people who were asked that question, 17 percent later
declared they had seen a barn. Only about 3 percent of people who
had not been exposed to the leading question later said the film
had included a barn.
   In another experiment, up to 80 percent of misled witnesses
recalled planted information.
   People can be quite confident that they are truly remembering
planted details, Loftus said.
   ``People have recalled non-existent broken glass and tape
recorders, a clean-shaven man as having a mustache, straight hair
as curly,'' she said.
   In an interview, she acknowledged that the degree of memory
distortion achieved by such experiments is far less ambitious than
the goals she described for the Chinese government.
   But the Chinese leaders have advantages over experimenters like
herself, she said.
   ``They have forever to do it,'' she said. ``I have only one
hour. They have the resources and the opportunity to just hammer
away at this in ways we haven't even begun to try in experiments.
   ``We present information once or twice, and people grab onto it.
They can wait and let memories fade for a year. What's left, except
this germ of a recollection, into which you can insert ... new
ideas.''
   Not everyone in her audience agreed with Loftus about the
Chinese government's ability to alter memories.
   ``I'm not as pessimistic about the eyewitnesses,'' said Sam
Glucksberg, a psychology professor at Princeton University.
   ``A person who was right next to a person who was shot, I don't
think his memory of that can be significantly altered,'' Glucksberg
said. ``I don't think you can convince him he did not see that.''
   Glucksberg said the impact on memory Loftus described are real,
but that nobody knows how much memories can be changed.
</TEXT>
