<DOCNO> AP890812-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SlainActivist 1stLd-Writethru a0455 08-12 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slain Activist, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0455,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funeral Procession Backs Efforts of Slain Anti-Drug Crusader</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with funeral, march, quotes from
minister and mayor. Picks up 5th graf, `On Friday...' Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 people chanting ``drug dealers got to
go'' followed the hearse of a slain anti-drug activist this morning
through the Brooklyn neighborhood she tried to make safer for her
family.
   The two-mile procession followed a funeral Mass at which Maria
Hernandez, 34, was praised for her courage.
   ``She, with her family, attempted to create a place where all of
us may be able to live with dignity. And then that dream and that
vision was tragically and dramatically shattered,'' said the Rev.
Charles Ploch.
   Three mayoral candidates joined those who packed St. John the
Baptist Church for the funeral. Carlos Hernandez, who received a
death threat during his wife's wake on Friday, was in the front of
the church with two of the couple's three children.
   Mrs. Hernandez was shot Tuesday by a gunman who fired at least
five bullets into her family's apartment. She died six hours later.
   She and her husband had confronted drug dealers in their
neighborhood, and the killing is seen in the community as
retaliation for their efforts. Hernandez has vowed to continue the
fight.
   ``Those most important to the elimination of the drug scourge
are people like Maria and Carlos Hernandez,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch
said. ``The rest of this city should stand up and say to them, `You
are not alone.'''
   After the funeral, Koch's leading challenger in November's
election, David Dinkins, and about two dozen Guardian Angels joined
the group marching to Cypress Hills Cemetery for Mrs. Hernandez's
burial.
   On Friday, a wake for Mrs. Hernandez was interrupted when
someone called in a bomb threat at a Brooklyn funeral home.
   Police said a small number of mourners were evacuated while
bomb-sniffing dogs went through the home, but nothing was found.
   Mrs. Hernandez's husband had not yet arrived at the home when
the search took place, said a funeral home spokesman.
   Services resumed after police found no evidence of a bomb, Burns
said.
   Police, meanwhile, are investigating a feud between the
Hernandezes and their next-door neighbors.
   A grand jury Thursday indicted one of the neighbors, Raymond
Gonzalez, 42, who last month allegedly stabbed Hernandez after the
Hernandezes accused him of selling cocaine in front of their house.
He is also accused of threatening Hernandez with an Uzi submachine
gun.
   Gonzalez was arrested for both incidents on Aug. 4 and was in
jail when Mrs. Hernandez was killed, police said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
