<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-BerlinWall     08-12 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Berlin Wall,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Awaits Soviet Response on Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a statement Saturday
marking the 28th anniversary of the Berlin Wall, said he hoped for
a positive Soviet response to make Berlin ``a place of cooperation,
not a point of confrontation.''
   ``We observe this sad anniversary with renewed determination to
overcome the division of Berlin and of Europe,'' Bush said in the
statement from Camp David, Md. He called the wall, built in 1961 by
the East Germans to stem the exodus of its citizens, the ``relic of
a bygone era and a failed policy.''
   Bush, during a May trip to West Germany in May, told a cheering
crowd it was time to make Europe ``whole and free'' and called on
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to open up ``the rusting Iron
Curtain.''
   ``As I said in Mainz on May 31, we want Berlin to be a place of
cooperation, not a point of confrontation,'' Bush's statement
Saturday said. ``We have asked the Soviet Union, as part of its
four-party responsibilities for Berlin, to join us in achieving
these goals. We still await what we hope will be a positive
response.''
   He called the people of West Berlin ``courageous,'' saying they
``tend the precious fire of freedom as a example for us all.''
   Bush repeated the U.S. commitment ``to improving the lives of
Berliners and to bringing closer the day when the city is again
united,'' adding: ``Together with our British and French allies, we
have put forward an initiative to make such progress a reality.''
