<FIRST>u i AM-Tambo 1stLd-Writethru a0511 08-12 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tambo, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says ANC Leader Oliver Tambo Suffered a Stroke</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs with background at end. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Tambo, president of the African National
Congress, suffered a stroke in Zambia and was flown to London for
treatment, sources in the organization were quoted as saying
Saturday.
   A spokesman for the British company Lonrho PLC said Tambo was
flown to London on a company plane but would not say which hospital
was treating the 71-year-old black nationalist leader or describe
his condition.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, quoted
sources in the African National Congress as saying Tambo was
stricken Wednesday and flown to London Friday for treatment at a
private hospital.
   They were quoted as saying he was absent during a summit in
Zambia Thursday involving the presidents of Angola, Botswana,
Mozambique, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe, and leaders of the ANC,
the largest guerrilla organization fighting the white-run
government in South Africa.
   The British Foreign Office could not immediately confirm the
report.
   The Lonrho spokesman, speaking anonymously, said the aircraft
had been in Lusaka for another reason and that action had been
taken to help Tambo after a request ``from African governments.''
   The Lonhro spokesman said he did not know how long Tambo would
be in Britain or whether the company would provide him with a
flight back to Zambia.
   Of the decision to use the Lonhro plane, he said:
   ``There was no hesitation. It was a matter of some considerable
concern that he should be got back to Britain as soon as possible.
The plane was coming in this direction anyway.''
   Tambo, leader of the ANC since 1967, has been in exile since
South Africa banned the organization in 1960.
   His longtime friend and jailed former ANC partner Nelson Mandela
said in a note from prison in 1985: ``Oliver Tambo is much more
than a brother to me. He is my greatest friend and comrade for
nearly 50 years.''
   Tambo is believed to command wide respect from others in the
ANC's exiled leadership, but there are persistent reports that two
factions will vie for power once he is gone.
   A more militant faction, headed by ANC military chief of staff
Chris Hani, has favored continuing or escalating sabotage and
bombings in South Africa, including attacks on civilian targets.
   The more moderate faction, favoring diplomacy, is led by Thabo
Mbeki, the ANC's foreign affairs secretary, who has been mentioned
frequently as a likely successor to Tambo.
</TEXT>
