<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages     08-12 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Cleric Says Hostage Issue Will Meet `Rational Solution'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's most influential Shiite
Moslem cleric said Saturday the hostage issue will ``move in the
direction of a rational solution.'' But he warned it could take a
long time, and any U.S. military move would backfire.
   Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah made his comments in an
interview with the Moslem-run radio Voice of the Nation a day after
he offered to help free Western hostages if Western countries
helped release Arab prisoners in Israel.
   Fadlallah is spiritual guide to the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God. The group is believed to be the umbrella organization
for underground factions holding most of the Western hostages in
Lebanon.
   Asked to comment on reports of a planned U.S. military action if
another American hostage is killed, Fadlallah said:
   ``This will not achieve anything but will endanger the hostages
for whom the war is waged and will increase the possibilities of
what America calls terrorism.
   ``We believe that any American military action will backfire and
may provoke revolutionary elements opposed to the American policy
in the region,'' he said.
   ``Therefore, the issue will move in the direction of a rational
solution that may take a long time, but it will not move at all in
a military atmosphere, at least in America's interests,'' he added.
   The United States sent warships to the eastern Mediterranean and
to waters near Iran during the height of the latest hostage crisis.
   The crisis developed after Israel abducted a
Hezbollah-affiliated cleric, Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, from south
Lebanon on July 28. Israeli officials say Obeid has since confessed
to helping plan attacks on Israel and to the 1988 abduction of U.S.
Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins, a U.N. peacekeeper in south
Lebanon.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth claimed it hanged
Higgins on July 31 because Israel refused to free Obeid. However,
some reports say he was killed months earlier.
   Another group, the Revolutionary Justice Organization, said it
would kill American hostage Joseph Cicippio if Obeid was not
released. However, it later said it had granted Cicippio a
reprieve, and offered to free him if Israel released Obeid and 450
Arab prisoners and also let 55 Palestinian deportees return to the
occupied lands.
   Israel has said any swap must include three Israeli soldiers
held in Lebanon.
   In his remarks Saturday, Fadlallah also accused the United
States of ``prolonging the detention'' of the hostages.
   ``America could have resolved this problem realistically through
deep, quiet diplomacy .... But instead it has worked on prolonging
the period of their detention because it found out it could use the
hostage issue in its ... war against terrorism,'' Fadlallah said.
   On Friday, Fadlallah said, ``Let us get to an agreement together
so that each side would use his own means and influence to end the
crisis of the hostages _ all hostages _ and resolve the problem of
Arab prisoners,'' he said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater and State Department
spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Fadlallah's statement was worth
noting.
   Among the 16 Western hostages in Lebanon are eight Americans,
four Britons, two West Germans, one Irishman and one Italian.
Longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of
The Associated Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
