<FIRST>r i AM-Priest-Award 1stLd-Writethru a0499 08-12 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Priest-Award, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Priest Wins Journalism Award in Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 1 graf at end to name foundation that gave award. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American priest whose writings and
broadcasts outraged former President Ferdinand Marcos has won the
1989 Ramon Magsaysay award for Journalism, Literature and Creative
Arts, it was announced Saturday.
   The Rev. James Bertram Reuter Jr. was praised for ``employing
his gifts as writer, theatrical director and broadcaster, but most
of all as teacher to make the performing arts and media a vital
force for the good of the Philippines.''
   Reuter, 73, of New Jersey, began directing plays in 1941 and
wrote scripts for a Catholic radio program. During World War II, he
wrote songs and skits to rally fellow inmates at Japanese prison
camps in the country.
   He was ordained in the United States in 1946 and returned to the
Philippines to teach journalism, write and direct art productions.
   He introduced Catholic programming on television and helped set
up the church's radio station, Veritas. When Marcos declared
martial law in 1972, Reuter was arrested for criticizing the
government.
   In the 1986 presidential elections, Reuter and several other
Catholic broadcasters counted ballots on their own to guard against
fraud.
   Weeks later, in the ensuing military revolt that toppled Marcos'
20-year government and catapulted Corazon Aquino to the presidency,
Reuter helped keep Veritas on the air so Filipinos could be
informed about what was happening.
   The award, bestowed by the Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation,
will be presented on Aug. 31, the 82nd birthday of the popular
Philippine president who died in a plane crash in 1957 and whose
name the foundation bears.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
