<DOCNO> AP890812-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1412EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TwainSymposium     08-12 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Twain Symposium,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scholars: Light and Dark Sides Are Secrets of Twain's Staying Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Mark Twain's humor is a chief
reason for his enduring popularity, several scholars meeting to
commemorate one of the author's least humorous novels said Twain's
brooding side will also help keep him relevant to future
generations.
   ``I think people are figuring out that they can't some day say,
`Well, Mark Twain, he's out of it. He was just a mindless
optimist,''' said Louis Budd, a Duke University professor and
editor of the ``Journal of American Literature.''
   ``People do know there was a darker and more irreverent side to
Mark Twain,'' Budd said.
   Budd was among about 150 literary scholars and Twain fans
attending a three-day conference sponsored by Elmira College's
Center for Mark Twain Studies at Quarry Farm to mark the 100th
anniversary of the publication of ``A Connecticut Yankee in King
Arthur's Court.''
   The conference, held Thursday, Friday and Saturday in the city
where Twain is buried, showed how popular the author remains 79
years after his death.
   ``Only a few years ago, academic types like myself were polled
on who was the greatest American writer and Mark Twain and Walt
Whitman came out No. 1,'' said Everett Emerson, a University of
North Carolina professor and Twain biographer.
   ``Now, in fact, I've almost never known an ordinary person who's
read a whole lot of Walt Whitman,'' he said. ``But Twain is
recognized by professors as a very great writer at the same time
ordinary people do, too. Twain's different from any other American
writer because he's liked by ordinary people.''
   Indeed, debates continued throughout the conference about the
meaning and significance of ``A Connecticut Yankee'' as if the
novel had appeared in 1989 instead of 1889.
   The novel concerns an imaginary trip to 6th-century England by
Hank Morgan, a Connecticut factory mechanic who uses his knowledge
of electricity and other ``modern'' technology to seize control of
the court.
   While the first third of the book is mostly a farce about the
customs of medieval England and the inconveniences of living in
that age, the novel takes on a more ominous tone in its final
two-thirds. It ends with a bloody battle in which thousands of
knights are slaughtered with the help of such 19th century
refinements as electricity and Gatling guns.
   Frederick Crews, a University of California at Berkeley
professor, said the ending of the book ``stuns and chills us.''
   ``Only a few critics have been able to talk themselves out of
the sense that something has gone terribly wrong, not only with the
book but also with Twain,'' he told conference participants.
   Many critics have seen the darkness of the latter part of ``A
Connecticut Yankee'' as presaging the final two troubled decades of
Twain's own life, when a series of financial and personal setbacks
prompted a string of bitter, misanthropic writings. Budd referred
to this stage of the author's life as the ``late, atheistic,
outrageous Twain.''
   Still, Crews and most other experts at the conference agreed
that many passages in ``A Connecticut Yankee'' exhibit the kind of
homespun wit and humor Twain became famous for in ``The Adventures
of Huckleberry Finn'' and other books.
   ``It has the makings of a classic,'' he said of ``A Connecticut
Yankee.''
   According to Emerson, Twain's reputation has profited from the
added attention the author has received from centennial
celebrations of ``Huckleberry Finn'' in 1985 and ``A Connecticut
Yankee'' this year.
   ``You must know the worst thing that could happen to a writer is
to be forgotten,'' he said. ``No one has forgotten this guy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890812-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1420EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Concert     08-12 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Concert,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Metal Separates Iron Curtain With Moscow Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet fans jumped, danced and wrapped themselves
in giant American flags Saturday as some of heavy metal's biggest
stars made their Soviet debut in Moscow's biggest-ever hard rock
concert.
   The benefit concert, a two-day extravaganza billed as the
``Moscow Music Peace Festival'' and likened to the Woodstock
festival of 20 years ago, features Western musicians Motley Crue,
Bon Jovi, Scorpions, Cinderella, Ozzy Osbourne, and Skid Row as
well as the Soviet groups Nuance, Gorky Park and Brigada S.
   Proceeds will go to programs that fight drug and alcohol abuse
in the United States and the Soviet Union.
   About 100,000 fans filled the Lenin Stadium in central Moscow
Saturday, many of them reclining on mats or jumping and screaming
near the stage, painted in the psychedelic style of the 1960s.
   Some fans wrapped themselves in giant American flags and formed
human pyramids.
   ``We're athletes, we need some psychological relaxation!'' a
member of the Soviet junior fencing team shouted after the pyramid
he was forming with teammates toppled.
   The concert's Soviet organizer, impressario Stas Namin, told a
news conference Friday the concert would be as important to his
generation as Woodstock was to American youth in 1969.
   ``We will show that rock is not just negative,'' he said.
``After so many years of stigmatization, this is something
positive,''
   At $16 a ticket, the concert was exorbitantly priced by Soviet
standards. However, organizers said it quickly sold out.
   ``This is the first time we've ever had such a concert,'' said
23-year-old Yelena Viklova, who came with her husband. ``There was
no way we could pass up the chance. We came to see the foreign
groups.''
   Rock promoter Alexei Kisilev said the concert represented a
major step forward from two years ago, when Soviet authorities
banned a proposed anti-drug concert because ``they said we didn't
have a drug problem, and our rock was not developed enough.''
   Soviet authorities no longer emphatically condemn rock music as
a decadent Western force, but officials still occasionally express
disapproval of rock culture.
   Few hard rock albums are put out in the Soviet Union, and groups
have generally had a hard time making arrangements for concert
halls and tours. They have, however, gained ground under President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's cultural thaw.
   Any parallel with Woodstock, the outdoor festival at a farm in
New York state that became a symbol of the 1960's, escaped many of
Saturday's fans. One 18-year-old Muscovite asked whether Woodstock
had been held in Moscow.
   Kisilev said the weekend's concert could change the Soviet rock
scene and serve as a precedent for more such events.
   One fan at the concert was U.S. ambassador Jack Matlock, who
gave an impromptu press conference wearing one of the ``Just Say
Nyet'' buttons promoters had distributed. The buttons mirrored the
U.S. anti-drug slogan ``Just Say `No.'''
   ``These contacts show we have common goals and common
problems,'' Matlock said as he posed for photos with long-haired
rockers Eric Brittingham and Fred Courey of Cinderella.
   The concert will spawn an album dedicated to rock stars who died
of overdoses. American viewers will be able to see four hours of
performances on cable television Sunday, organizers said.
</TEXT>
