<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter Mondale has
been named a director of Northwest Airlines' parent company.
   New owner Alfred Checchi has a sincere commitment to the
airline, the former vice president said Friday, shortly before his
appointment to the NWA Inc. board was formally announced.
   ``He persuaded me that, where he was going to take the airline,
I wanted to go,'' said Mondale, also a former U.S. senator from
Minnesota who now pratices law in Minneapolis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed construction worker was
sentenced to 16 months in jail for stealing singer Barbra
Streisand's 1976 Mercedes-Benz.
   Olin Lipscomb Jr., 35, pleaded guilty last month to one count of
theft and unlawful driving of a vehicle.
   Superior Court Commissioner Florence Cooper dismissed two other
charges of grand theft auto and evading arrest in sentencing
Lipscomb on Friday.
   Lipscomb took the car July 5 after Streisand's secretary parked
it on a street, police said.
   Officers spotted the car about four hours later and gave chase.
Lipscomb lost control of the vehicle and struck the patrol car. The
Mercedes suffered moderate damage and Lipscomb cut his finger. The
officers were unhurt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire publisher Malcolm
Forbes rode his green and gold motorcycle through a dealership and
hobnobbed with bikers en route to the Black Hills Motorcycle
Classic in Sturgis.
   Forbes, 69, riding a Harley-Davidson, said Friday he was making
a return visit to the motorcycle rally, which attracts thousands of
bikers every year.
   ``I guess it's the same thing that makes everyone keep coming
back _ it's a mecca for anyone who loves Harleys. I'm one of the
many with the good sense to enjoy it,'' Forbes said.
   ``He's a symbol that you're never too old to ride,'' Paul
Sjoquist, a 56-year-old Minneapolis lawyer, said. ``I'm a
professional person myself and I enjoy seeing someone like that
ride. The sport of riding needs respectability and he has given it
that.
   ``He's just a regular sort of guy. A very nice man.''
   Forbes, whose wealth has been estimated as high as $1 billion,
took over the Forbes magazine company in 1964.
   He says he didn't ride a motorcycle until he was 48 and now has
70 of the machines.
   ``I was afraid to try,'' he said. ``For the last 21 years I've
been making up for lost time.''
   Forbes also brought with him a purple Harley-Davidson 883 _ the
bike he gave to his friend, actress Elizabeth Taylor.
   ``It's purple passion. Just like her perfume,'' Forbes said,
adding that Taylor would not attend the rally in Sturgis.
   He said his relationship with Taylor was friendly. ``A very
happy and enjoyable friendship continues. She's going with me to
Morocco next Tuesday.''
   Forbes plans to celebrate his 70th birthday next Saturday at a
$2 million party for 600 at his Palais Mendoub in Tangier, Morocco.
