<FIRST>r a AM-RapArrests     08-12 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rap Arrests,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Men With Rapper LL Cool J Charged With Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A singer and two crew members with LL Cool
J's rap band were charged with raping a 15-year-old girl who
attended an after-concert party after going backstage on a pass won
in a radio contest.
   The girl told authorities that six to eight men taunted her
during the assault and made comments such as, ``When's it going to
be our turn?''
   Singer David James Parker, 26, and band technician Gary Chris
Saunders, 22, both of New York City, and bodyguard Christopher
Elias Tsipouras, 26, of Union, N.J., were charged Friday with
first-degree criminal sexual conduct, said Kevin Johnson, assistant
Hennepin County attorney.
   LL Cool J, whose real name is James Todd Smith, was not involved
in the incident after Wednesday night's concert and did not meet
the 15-year-old, police said. He and the rest of his group were
continuing their three-month national tour.
   They three who were charged were being held Saturday at the
Hennepin County jail under $100,000 bail each. They were scheduled
for court appearances Monday, Johnson said. The felony is
punishable by up to 20 years in prison and a $35,000 fine.
   ``We're going to try to find out who else was in the room,''
Johnson said. ``If we can learn who they are, they could be
charged, too,'' as accomplices.
   The girl and a 16-year-old female friend received backstage
passes along with tickets to Wednesday's concert when one of them
won a radio station's contest. They accompanied group members in a
limousine to L'Hotel Sofitel in Bloomington for the party on
Tsipouras' promise he would introduce them to LL Cool J,
authorities said.
   Sexual advances were made to the girls, and the 16-year-old
left, Bloomington police Sgt. Michael Jennings said. The younger
girl could not escape and eventually was sexually assaulted by
three men, the sergeant said.
   ``They were overwhelmed by the celebrity status and all the
flash,'' said Johnson. ``I think they were naive enough to go into
the hotel thinking they would meet LL Cool J.''
   The girl was crying and screaming during the incident, and other
people were coming and going from the hotel room, Detective Dan
Laurila said.
   The three men were arrested early Thursday morning.
   The radio station, KDWB, is reviewing its practice of awarding
backstage passes, said general manager Gary Swartz, who said he was
outraged by the incident.
   LL Cool J, short for Ladies Love Cool James, is among the best
known rappers, and has a current hit, ``Walking With a Panther.''
His songs are known for explicit lyrics involving sexual conquests
and macho stereotypes.
</TEXT>
