<FIRST>r i AM-India-Ethnic     08-12 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Ethnic,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Battles Kill 95, Force 60,000 to Flee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SABITA GOSWAMI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUWAHATI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Battles between tribesmen and native
Assamese in northeastern India have left at least 95 people dead,
witnesses and news reports said Saturday. One official said 60,000
residents had fled.
   The warring sides fought with spears, bows and arrows, and
homemade guns, said a witness to the clashes at Gohpur.
   ``It was like an ancient war,'' said Dibya Kalita, who fled to
Guwahati to escape the violence. Gohpur is 112 miles northeast of
this capital city of Assam state.
   The Bodo tribesmen, who are of Mongol origin, are campaigning
for a separate homeland in Assam, a remote state bordering
Bangladesh.
   The Press Trust of India news agency said Saturday that 95
bodies have been found in the area. It said the clashes had raged
over the past four days.
   Officials reported five deaths, but their count was believed to
be much too low.
   The Assam director-general of police, S.V. Subramanium,
confirmed reports of the battles but said he was awaiting details.
   The Assamese backlash at Gohpur started after 10 Assamese were
burnt to death in a neighboring area. Bodo militants were blamed
for the deaths.
   Hundreds of Bodo homes in 20 villages were set on fire, forcing
residents to flee to neighboring Arunachal Pradesh state.
   A state government spokesman in the state capital, Itanagar,
said 60,000 Bodos had crossed the state border since Wednesday.
   ``We are trying to provide them with shelter, but we fear more
will come over,'' one official said by telephone from Guwahati. The
official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Bodos, mostly farmers, were animists before they converted
earlier this century to Christianity and Hinduism, India's dominant
religion. The Bodos make up about 30 percent of Assam's 20 million
people.
   The proposed Bodoland would cover about one-third of Assam's
territory.
   The government has refused to consider the Bodo demand for a
separate homeland but says it is willing to talk to militants about
ending the violence.
   Some Bodos began demanding a homeland more than two decades ago,
but there were very few reports of violence until recent years.
   In a related development, Bodo militants killed eight Assamese
policemen and wounded six in Nalbari district about 40 miles from
Guwahati, police said Saturday.
   The policemen were killed when the militants used a
remote-control bomb to blow up their jeep.
   No arrests were reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
