<SECOND>AM-BRF--Fatal Fire,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rules City Not Liable For Fire That Killed 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury found the city was not negligent in the
death of a 20-month-old boy who was one of 12 people who died in a
1987 house fire.
   A Milwaukee County Circuit Court jury deliberated for five hours
Friday night before ruling against Jill Schreck, who sued the city
in connection with the death of her toddler son, Anthony.
   Ms. Schreck claimed the city was negligent because a building
inspector, who was at the one-family house three weeks before the
fire, did not tell another resident, Annie Phillips, that smoke
detectors were the responsibility of the tenants.
   The jury ruled Ms. Schreck and Ms. Phillips, both survivors of
the blaze, each was 50 percent negligent.
   ``It's over with,'' Ms. Schreck cried when approached by
reporters after the verdict was announced. ``My son's gone and I'm
the one that _ just leave me alone.''
   Testimony at the trial conflicted on whether there were working
smoke alarms at the time of the fire.
