<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1609EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     08-12 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Botha Appears Isolated in Power Struggle With Heir Apparent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governing party leader F.W. de
Klerk indicated Saturday his Cabinet colleagues supported him as a
showdown approached in a leadership struggle with outgoing
President P.W. Botha.
   Political commentators said the seemingly isolated Botha might
quit under pressure or try to assert himself at a Cabinet meeting
Monday by firing de Klerk, who replaced the president in February
as head of the National Party.
   De Klerk is expected to succeed Botha as president after
parliamentary elections on Sept. 6.
   One opposition leader, Andries Treurnicht of the far-right
Conservative Party, said de Klerk was leading a ``palace
revolution'' against Botha and suggested the president could fire
any rebellious ministers.
   Relations between Botha and de Klerk have been strained for
months, but the rift intensified Friday when the president
announced tersely he had not been consulted about de Klerk's
planned diplomatic mission to Zambia on Aug. 28.
   De Klerk met for nearly three hours Saturday with almost the
entire Cabinet at his home in Pretoria, then announced that the
ministers had reached a unanimous decision how to handle the
dispute when Botha convenes a full Cabinet meeting on Monday in
Cape Town.
   De Klerk refused to elaborate on the decision, but said: ``The
National Party does not in the least underestimate the seriousness
of the situation.''
   The dispute has deeply embarrassed the party at a crucial stage
in election campaign and has virtually eliminated any chance for
Botha, 73, to exit gracefully after 11 years in power.
   De Klerk and Foreign Minister Pik Botha have been invited to
meet with Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda, a longtime critic of
South Africa's racial segregation policies, The meeting has been
hailed as a potentially historic breakthrough for South Africa, and
Pik Botha announced Saturday that the trip would proceed despite
the leadership dispute.
   The meeting of Cabinet members at de Klerk's home was viewed as
a direct challenge by the education minister against the president.
Under the Constitution, only the president can convene a formal
Cabinet meeting, although the ministers all are National Party
members who owe political loyalty to de Klerk.
   Pierre Claassen, political writer for the independent South
African Press Association, reported that National Party
officeholders were united in ``ill-concealed anger'' at President
Botha.
   Leaders of the liberal and far-right white opposition parties,
hoping for major gains in the elections, said the dispute reflected
chaos atop the National Party, which has held power since 1948.
   Kaunda made the initial announcement of the Aug. 28 meeting. Pik
Botha, the foreign minister, subsequently confirmed the plans and
said the arrangements were made in consultation with President
Botha.
   The president, in a two-sentence statement Friday, in effect
called his foreign minister a liar.
   ``I am not aware, in terms of the rules governing overseas
journeys by (Cabinet) ministers, of the discussions to be held on
28 August as announced by Dr. Kaunda,'' the president said.
   Newspapers reported Saturday that Pik Botha was braced for the
possibility that the president might fire him. The Star of
Johannesburg said the entire Cabinet might resign if any minister,
including de Klerk, were fired. The Citizen, another Johannesburg
daily, said the president could resign ``at any moment.''
   The leadership rift surfaced when Botha resigned as National
Party leader after suffering a stroke in January. Party officials
backed de Klerk in a power struggle focusing on how soon Botha
would retire.
   De Klerk's planned meeting with Kaunda is seen as important
because the Zambian is chairman of the six-nation Frontline States,
established for the purpose of confronting South Africa's white-led
government.
   Kaunda reportedly may offer to arrange a summit of all states in
the region, including South Africa, if de Klerk commits his
government to negotiating with the African National Congres.
   The ANC, headquartered in Zambia, has waged a bombing and
sabotage campaign since 1961 aimed at ending white-minority rule in
South Africa and gaining full political rights for the black
majority.
</TEXT>
