<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 1623EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Leland     08-12 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Leland,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Search Fails to Find Congressional Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0543</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ethiopia-Leland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon on Saturday dispatched five more
aircraft and 100 more people to Ethiopia to help search for Rep.
Mickey Leland, and his office chief backed off earlier criticism of
the rescue effort by saying she is now ``tremendously gratified''
by it.
   Navy Capt. Stan Bloyer declared ``we're not anywhere close'' to
scaling down the hunt for Leland, D-Texas, and 15 others, whose
chartered Twin Otter vanished Monday on a flight from Addis Ababa
to a refugee camp near the Sudan border about 270 miles
west-southwest of the capital.
   ``We're going to apply all the resources we can use,'' said
Bloyer, former air operations chief of the Sixth Fleet and now with
the Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``We're going to continue to operate on
the premise that there are survivors.''
   Bloyer said the U.S. team is again concentrating its search,
including photo-reconnaissance flights by U-2 spy planes, along
Leland's planned flight path, after concluding that two earlier
leads, involving faint signals detected both north and south of
Addis Ababa by weather satellites, were merely false readings.
   As of Saturday, the U.S. military had one C-141 medical
evacuation aircraft, two HC-130 search and rescue aircraft, and
four MH-60 search and rescue helicopters, equipped with special
night-vision gear, stationed in Ethiopia, along with 165 men and
women, Bloyer said. He reported that two more HC-130s, one EC-130
command and control aircraft and two C-141 transports were on the
way, along with 100 more people, and would arrive Sunday.
   The latest contingent includes Maj. Gen. James F. Record,
director of operations of the U.S. Central Command at MacDill Air
Force Base in Florida, who will coordinate the American team.
   Coupled with the efforts of Ethiopia, Bloyer said, ``I'm not
aware of any search and rescue effort in the world that's involved
this many airplanes.''
   But he noted that the effort continues to be dogged by poor
weather, limiting the usefulness of the 6,000 feet of film returned
from each of the U-2 overflights, and hampering the visibility of
the lower-flying rescue fleet.
   Two U-2 flights have yielded no results, and a third U-2 mission
was flown Saturday. Each flight lasts 10 hours, with just two of
those over the search area, and developing and analyzing the huge
amount of film requires many additional hours.
   In Washington, meanwhile, Leland's press secretary and office
chief, Alma Newsom, retreated from her angry criticism Friday of
the rescue effort.
   Following reassurances later Friday from President Bush and
others, she said, the staff is convinced that a ``commitment and
sense of urgency are now operating at all levels. We are
tremendously gratified by that.''
   Ms. Newsom had said Friday that ``we have seen motion, we have
seen some action, but we have also seen a lot of missteps,'' adding
that ``we could have and should have located them by now.''
   Saturday, in voice weakened by laryngitis, she said: ``I was
somewhat astounded and not a little distressed that some had
interpreted my remarks yesterday as being anti-military _ anti-our
men and women in the military. Nothing could be further from the
truth. We all believe that ... when the U.S. armed forces come to
the rescue, they have no peer.''
   Bloyer said that while U.S. authorities have permission to
operate in the skies over Sudan, the main search effort will
continue to be focused inside Ethiopia for the time being.
``Certainly it is possible the airplane proceeded into Sudan, and
we will be exploring that in due course,'' he said.
   Until now, he said, the U.S. planes have used ``techniques that
would give a 50 percent probability of detection,'' in the primary
search area. ``We're changing now to a much slower and deliberate
mode, which should give us n 80-90 percent capability of
detection,'' he explained.
   The four helicopters, flown in from Eglin Air Force Base in
Florida, are equipped with infrared devices and crews trained in
night vision, but regular night flights likely won't begin until
Monday, weather allowing, when relief crews are available, he said.
   As it is, the choppers are flying throughout the daylight hours,
with mid-air refueling from the HC-130s, he said.
   Earlier in the week, hopes were raised that either of the two
signals monitored via satellite had come from the plane's emergency
beacon. But Bloyer explained that the only ground station able to
monitor the satellite data as it passed over Ethiopia is in India,
so far away that ``it's on the very fringes of the ability'' to
decipher the signal correctly.
   Sophisticated electronic gear on lower-flying U.S. planes found
no signals at the two locations, and, moreover, no evidence was
found in either area by thousand of Ethiopian troops which combed
them on oot, he said.
   Bloyer noted, however, that the plane's emergency beacon would
begin to deteriorate after 72 hours, and any ``usable signal''
likely would disappear in a week as the transmitter's batteries
wore down.
</TEXT>
