<HEAD>Explosion in Arctic Island Mine Kills Five Soviet Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coal mine explosion killed five Soviet
workers and injured two on Norway's Svalbard Islands, the Norwegian
news agency NTB said Saturday.
   Details of Friday's accident were not known but it was probably
caused when methane gas in the mine ignited, Magnus Storhaug of the
Svalbard governor's office told NTB on Saturday.
   The Soviets reported the accident to the governor of the Arctic
archipelago on Saturday. NTB quoted Storhaug as saying this was the
first time the Soviets informed Norway of an accident on the island.
   The mine is owned by Trust Artikuol, a Soviet company operating
on the Norwegian islands, 400 miles northwest of Norway. The
Soviets and other countries were granted access to the Norwegian
islands under a 1925 treaty.
