<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass Meeting in Azerbaijan Calls For Warning Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rallied in the southern
republic of Azerbaijan Saturday to demand the removal of Soviet
troops from an mainly Armenian area of the republic, activists said.
   Demonstrators in the Azerbaijani capital of Baku called for a
strike and another protest Monday if authorities fail to meet their
demands, said Mamedgassan Gambarov, a member of the Azerbaijani
People's Front.
   Gambarov, speaking by telephone from Baku, said other demands
entailed the recall of unpopular Azerbaijani deputies to the Soviet
parliament and the cancellation of curfews throughout the Caucasus
republic.
   Moslem activist Almaz Yestekov said the front was asking for the
removal of Soviet troops from Nagorno-Karabakh, a mainly Christian
Armenian enclave in traditionally Shiite Moslem Azerbaijan.
   Disputes over the area, which neighboring Armenia wants to
annex, have led to violence several times in the last 18 months,
causing authorities to impose curfews and bring in troops to keep
order. Scores of people have been killed and thousands fled their
homes.
   Slogans at Saturday's protest included ``Karabakh and Azerbaijan
are indivisible'' according to Yestekov, who said he heads a
fledgling news agency specializing in Moslem areas of the Soviet
Union.
   Activists said thousands of people attended the rally, but they
gave no specific figure.
   Speakers also called for authorities to give the People's Front
full legal status as an organization, Yestekov said.
   People's Front groups have sprung up in many of the 15 Soviet
republics in an effort to push local demands for autonomy. They
have become especially strong in the Baltic republics.
