<SECOND>AM-Bridge Deaths,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Suspected of Throwing Three Children Off 100-Foot Bridge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drownings, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former mental patient apparently threw
her three young children to their death off a 100-foot bridge then
jumped in herself, police said.
   Seachers found the third body in the Tombigbee River on
Saturday, and police said homicide charges were likely against
their mother, Regina Moss Monroe, 22.
   Mrs. Monroe was listed in serious condition at a hospital where
she was treated for exposure and bruises.
   Police Chief Bill Taylor said authorities discovered Mrs. Monroe
along the banks of the river Friday, some 19 hours after she last
was seen atop the McCorquodale Bridge with her three children.
   ``She was sitting down in the water,'' Lt. Charles Burge said.
   ``We have some witnesses who saw her on the bridge, and she
apparently made some statements to the rescue squad regarding her
actions,'' said Taylor.
   Taylor said the body of Alicia Monroe, 5, was found downstream
from the bridge Saturday morning. The bodies of James Monroe Jr.,
3, and his sister Jessica Monroe, also 3, were found Friday.
   Mrs. Monroe was found in shallow water near the bridge where her
car, its motor still running and front doors open, was found
Thursday night.
   Mrs. Monroe's husband, James Monroe Sr., alerted police after he
came out of a store about 11 p.m. Thursday and found the car with
his wife and three children gone.
   Monroe flagged down a passing police car and told the officer
his wife had apparently driven off with their children, Burge said.
Monroe, 31, told police his wife had mental problems and had been a
patient in a mental hospital, said Burge.
