<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-12 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>3-Year Old Shot Dead During Gaza Confrontations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stray bullet by an Israeli soldier killed a
3-year-old girl playing in a Gaza Strip refugee camp where troopers
battled stone-throwing Palestinians, Arab reports said Saturday.
The army confirmed the death but said it was checking the
circumstances.
   Masked Palestinians killed two Arabs suspected of collaborating
with Israeli authorities in the West Bank, stabbing one and hanging
the other in a school courtyard, the army and Arab reports said.
   At least 11 Palestinians were wounded by gunfire in
confrontations with the army in the Gaza Strip, hospital officials
said. Three others were shot and wounded in West Bank clashes,
radio and Arab reports said.
   The army said it was checking the reports of wounded.
   The reported deaths Saturday would raise to 535 the number of
Palestinians killed by Israeli troops or civilians since the
Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8, 1987. In addition, 94
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs who suspected them of
collaborating with Israel. Thirty-eight Israeli Jews have been
killed.
   Bothina Adib Hejow, 3, was killed by a stray bullet from one of
the troopers who dispersed stone-throwers in the Khan Younis
refugee camp, Arab reports said. The reports said the girl was
playing in the camp's main road nearby when she was hit.
   The army said the girl was killed but it was still investigating
the circumstances.
   At least three others were shot and wounded in the Khan Younis
clash, doctors said.
   In the Askar refugee camp near Nablus, the largest West Bank
city, masked Palestinians repeatedly stabbed Murshed Kaniery, 55,
after accusing him of collaborating with Israeli security forces,
Arab reports said. He died later in a Nablus hospital.
   In Bidiya village near Tulkarem in the West Bank, masked Arabs
hanged 30-year-old school teacher Jamal Taha in his school's
courtyard, the reports said.
   The army confirmed the two deaths and said it was checking the
circumstances.
   Palestinians said the army imposed a curfew on Bidiya after the
early-morning killing and deployed hundreds of troops to search the
village and surrounding fields for the attackers.
   Also Saturday, troops dispersed a march of 200 Palestinian
activists in the West Bank Balata refugee camp. The army fired
bullets and used a gravel-spewing cannon to disperse the
demonstrators, Arab reports said.
   On Friday night in southern Lebanon, Israeli troops and allied
Lebanese militiamen shot and wounded a guerrilla whose unit planned
to infiltrate Israel, the army said. The wounded man was captured,
but his companions escaped.
   The clash occurred 1{ miles from the Israeli settlement of
Misgav Am near the Lebanese border in Israel's self-declared
security zone. It was the third incident in the zone this month.
</TEXT>
