<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Arms     08-12 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Arms,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Talk of Giving New Arms to Afghan Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will give Afghanistan
new weapons and aircraft if it confirms that more U.S. arms have
reached guerrillas fighting to overthrow the government, a Soviet
envoy said Saturday.
   Filip Sydorski, the third-ranking Soviet diplomat in Kabul, said
he could not confirm an Afghan general's statement that the Soviet
Union is supplying Afghanistan with new MiG-29 fighters and the
latest Sukhoi ground-attack jets to defend the country against a
Pakistani attack. However, he said the MiG-29s could be part of new
shipments.
   The Afghan government claims the Moslem guerrillas are backed by
soldiers from Pakistan, which provides headquarters to the
guerrillas. Pakistan denies its troops are involved.
   In his remarks on Austrian television, Sydorski said, ``I'm sure
if tomorrow some new American weapons would appear on the soil of
Afghanistan, maybe the day after tomorrow, or a week after that,
new kinds of weapons including new aircraft, maybe MiG-29 ...,
would also appear in this country.''
   U.S. officials have been quoted as saying the guerrillas will be
receiving new weapons to counter highly effective bombing attacks
by the Afghan air force.
   On Thursday, Lt. Gen. Abdul Haq Ulumi, a member of the Afghan
Supreme Military Council, said a contract for Soviet MiG-29s and
Su-27 ground-attack jets had been completed.
   Soviet ambassador Yuli M. Vorontsov said in June that the Soviet
Union would be accepting an Afghan request for MiG-29s and Su-27s
if there was an escalation of fighting and border violations by
Pakistan.
   The United States and the Soviet Union are sponsors of the April
1988 Geneva accords. which provided for the withdrawal of Soviet
troops from Afghanistan on Feb. 15 and an end to outside
interference in Afghanistan.
   However, the Soviets and Americans have accused each other of
boosting arms shipments to their Afghan allies.
</TEXT>
