<FIRST>u a AM-Legislators-Wrapup     08-12 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Legislators-Wrapup,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Legislators Grapple With Issues On Local Horizon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State legislatures are under pressure to act
on a variety of issues, including abortion, lawmakers were told
during a national convention.
   The 5,000 delegates to the National Conference of State
Legislatures got the grim word from panelists and Bush
administration officials in dozens of sessions at the six-day
meeting, which ended Friday.
   Increased spending is the prescription for most of the ills, but
the states' economic future is clouded by large trade and federal
budget deficits, said Samuel Nunez Jr., Louisiana Senate president
pro tempore and president of the NCSL.
   Unfunded federal mandates have added billions of dollars in new
responsibilities for the states in recent years, Nunez said.
Federal welfare reform and changes in catastrophic health care and
nursing home legislation will also raise state costs, he said.
   A survey by NCSL staff showed that education makes up more than
50 percent of state budgets nationwide. The overall increase in
spending was 7.2 percent, up from 6.6 percent a year ago. Spending
on corrections rose 14.1 percent while the increase in Medicaid
costs was 10.4 percent.
   ``The greatest concentration of fiscal problems this year was in
the New England states and in New York and New Jersey, places that
just two years ago were faring better than most states,'' said Lee
Daniels, NCSL president-elect and minority leader of the Illinois
House.
   While some delegates claimed a continuing erosion of state
sovereignty by the federal government, one of the highest-profile
topics at the convention was an issue many legislators would rather
leave to the U.S. Supreme Court _ abortion.
   About 600 demonstrators, half of them chanting pro-choice
slogans and the other half singing hymns and carrying anti-abortion
placards, marched downtown Monday as delegates arrived for a social
event.
   In a July 3 decision in a Missouri case, the high court
implicitly invited states to enact their own laws on abortion 16
years after the court made abortion legal.
   ``It's not our business,'' Joan Lawrence, state representative
from Ohio, told a crowded session on Wednesday. ``We're going to be
making a serious mistake if we step into this swamp.''
   But Massachusetts state Sen. Paul White told lawmakers they
won't be able to steer clear of the issue.
   ``We're stuck with the fact that this is an issue that has to be
dealt with,'' White said. ``It isn't going to evaporate. It isn't
going to disappear.
   ``I don't think this is an issue about polls... or holding your
finger in the wind to see which way the wind is blowing,'' he said.
``I think this is an issue that you have to look within yourself.''
   U.S. Health and Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan, U.S.
Secretary of Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner and former
Environmental Protection Agency administrator William Ruckelshaus
also had advice for lawmakers.
   Sullivan called for more state spending to lower infant
mortality and Skinner urged states to raise local gasoline taxes
and spend more on highways. Ruckelshaus, now head of a large waste
disposal company, said lawmakers should show more backbone in
finding sites for solid waste landfills.
   Deputy Energy Secretary Henson Moore said his department will
design a ``road map'' for a national energy policy, but said many
of the policies must be implemented at the state level.
</TEXT>
