<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-12 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Coast Drenched by Thunderstorms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms drenched the East Coast on Saturday from North
Carolina to southern New England, flooding roads and causing other
problems and prompting flood watches for many other areas.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell from Florida to the
central Gulf Coast and from the southern High Plains to Minnesota
and the Dakotas. A few showers and thunderstorms fell over Idaho
and western Montana.
   Fair to partly sunny skies prevailed across the rest of the
nation.
   The torrential East Coast storms, which developed along a
stationary front, flooded subway tunnels and roads in New York
City, delaying trains and tieing up traffic.
   Nearly 3 inches of rain fell in New York between midnight and 3
p.m. Heavier rainfall totals for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT
included 1{ inches at Norfolk, Va., 1 inch at Salisbury, Md., and
nearly an inch at Dover, Del.
   A small stream and urban flood watch was in effect for all of
southern New Jersey, parts of eastern Pennsylvania, southern
Vermont and southeast New York state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 101 degrees at Phoenix. The low
for the Lower 48 states Saturday morning was 36 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   Sunday's foreast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
across the Rocky Mountains and the Great Plains, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes region, the eastern Gulf Coast,
the northern Atlantic Coast states, the middle Atlantic Coast,
upstate New York and northern New England.
   Fair to partly sunny skies were expected across the rest of the
nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the lower 90s in southern
Florida, southern Texas, southern New Mexico and the northern High
Plains; over 90 degrees across much of the nation west of the
Rockies, with readings above 100 degrees in the Southwestern
deserts; in the 70s across the northern Atlantic Coast; and in the
60s and 70s along the Pacific Coast.
</TEXT>
