<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 2010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-12 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Marks 6th Anniversary of Rule, Opposition Wants Him Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's
de facto leader, on Saturday quietly celebrated the sixth
anniversary of his command of Panama's Defense Forces.
   No public ceremonies marking the anniversary were announced by
the Noriega-controlled government or Defense Forces.
   The anniversary followed several confrontations between U.S.
military personnel and Defense Forces troopers in recent days.
   On Friday, a Panamanian patrol briefly detained U.S. military
police in four vehicles in the Curundu area near the Panama Canal.
Earlier last week, American troops blockaded Fort Amador, which
contains both U.S. and Panamanian military facilities.
   Noriega has rebuffed all U.S. efforts, including economic
sanctions, to force him to step down.
   Washington has exerted pressure to remove Noriega since two
federal grand juries in Florida indicted him on drug trafficking
and money laundering charges in February 1988. He denies the
charges.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in Washington Friday
that the Bush administration ``would not rule out'' seizing Noriega
and taking him to Florida to face drug trafficking charges. But
Fitzwater said Bush was not contemplating such a move at this time.
   Opposition leader Ricardo Arias Calderon told a news conference
Saturday the presidents of Colombia, Peru and Venezuela believe
that Noriega is the major obstacle to democracy in Panama.
   Calderon said he and Guillermo Ford met last week with the
presidents and other officials in those South American nations.
Calderon and Ford were the two vice presidential candidates on the
opposition slate in the May 7 elections.
   Calderon said the three presidents ``have a very clear idea that
popular sovereignty and national sovereignty cannot be dissociated
and they consider that only a free people can really be sovereign.''
   International observers said the opposition won the May election
by a landslide, but the government annulled the balloting a few
days later saying there had been vote fraud. Guillermo Endara was
the opposition's presidential candidate.
   The opposition has proposed a plebicite this month to allow
Panamanians to decide whether they want Noriega to continue in his
command.
   Noriega said Friday the proposal was tantamount to turning
Panama into ``a colony that accepts arrogance, vassalage and
indignity.''
   He made the comment in a speech at a parade of thousands of
troopers and paramilitary civilian units ending a 10-day exercise
called ``Zap the Intruder.''
   U.S. officials say the U.S. forces have the right to conduct
their own exercises under the 1977 Panama Canal treaties to assure
the security of the canal.
   Noriega claims the United States wants to abrogate the treaties,
which provide for the canal to be turned over to Panama at the end
of 1999.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
