<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Burma     08-12 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Burma,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Opposition Leader Gives Up Hunger Strike, Britain Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office said Saturday that Burmese
opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi had given up a hunger strike and
that her British husband and their children would return to Britain
in September.
   Ms. Suu Kyi, leader of Burma's main opposition political party,
is under house arrest by the military government. Her husband,
Oxford professor Michael Aris, flew to Burma to see her July 22 and
had not been allowed contact with British diplomats since. Britain
lodged a formal protest Aug. 4.
   On Saturday, Aris met with the British consul in Rangoon at a
Burmese military guest house in the presence of three Burmese
officials, the Foreign Office said.
   The Burmese government had said that under terms of Ms. Suu
Kyi's house arrest, members of her family are forbidden to make
contact with foreign embassies.
   Ms. Suu Kyi had been reported on hunger strike but no details
had emerged.
   The Foreign Office said that Aris told the consul his wife had
abandoned a protest hunger strike but would remain under house
arrest.
   She gave up the 2-week-old hunger strike after ``a solemn
assurance'' from Burmese officials about the safety of her
followers in the National League for Democracy, the Foreign Office
said.
   Ms. Suu Kyi, the daughter of slain independence leader Aung San,
has urged the military government to hold free elections and end
their 27-year rule in the former British colony. She was one of the
most popular speakers in nationwide protests for democracy last
year.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, speaking anonymously, said Burma was
being unacceptable when it insists that Aris consider himself under
the same restrictions as his wife if he chooses to stay in the
country.
   The couple's sons, Alexander, 16, and Kim, 13, subject to
similar restrictions, would be returning to Britain to continue
their education.
   Aris said he was applying for his visa to be extended beyond
next Saturday when it expires, the spokesman said. ``Depending on
his wife's continued well-being he intends to return to the United
Kingdom in early September.''
   The Foreign Office said the conditions of the meeting were ``not
entirely satisfactory,'' although the Burmese representatives did
not intervene.
   And the spokesman condemned the Burmese government's continued
``muzzling'' of Ms. Suu Kyi, the daughter of slain independence
leader Aung San.
</TEXT>
