<HEAD>Slain Anti-Drug Activist Described as Martyr</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-drug activist slain when a gunman opened
fire through her window was described Saturday as a martyr by
friends who vowed after her funeral to continue fighting to rid
their neighborhood of drugs.
   ``I know my wife, wherever she's at, is looking down on us and
will give us the strength we need so we can continue the fight,''
Carlos Hernandez said as he and hundreds of supporters arrived at
Cypress Hills Cemetery behind the hearse bearing Maria Hernandez's
pink coffin.
   ``Drug dealers gotta go!'' the crowd chanted along the two-mile
walk from the family's home in the borough of Brooklyn. Some
carried signs with slogans like: ``Death to drug dealers!''
   Mrs. Hernandez, a 34-year-old mother of three, was killed
Tuesday by a gunman who fired five bullets into her bedroom from
the street as she dressed for work.
   Authorities believe it was in retaliation for the anti-drug
efforts of the victim and her husband, who has received numerous
death threats.
   Mrs. Hernandez' wake was interrupted Friday when a bomb threat
was telephoned to the funeral home. Mourners were evacuated but no
bomb was found.
   ``We march through the streets of Brooklyn because we believe
that Maria's spirit has and does and will make a difference in our
community,'' the Rev. Charles Plock told mourners at St. John the
Baptist church Saturday. ``It will strengthen our resolve and stir
our community.''
   Among those attending the funeral Mass was Mayor Edward I. Koch,
who went to the pulpit and said the answer to the drug problem
won't be the military, the police or more drug education efforts.
   ``Those most important to the elimination of the drug scourge
are people like Maria and Carlos Hernandez,'' Koch said. The city
should tell Hernandez and others with the courage to take a stand,
``You are not alone,'' he added.
   After the funeral, friends and supporters gathered in front of
the Hernandez's home. Police estimated as many as 300 people
marched on foot, while behind them were dozens of cars.
   Jacqueline Perez, a family friend, said she and her children
were marching so that Hernandez would know ``that people are with
him. This has to be stopped, one way or another.''
   ``She really died a martyr,'' said a 28-year-old administrative
assistant and marcher who declined to give her name, saying she is
active in the fight against drugs in her own neighborhood.
</TEXT>
