<FIRST>u i AM-China-Dissident     08-12 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissident,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Chinese Student Leader Predicts New Revolt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese student leader who fled after
pro-democracy demonstrators were killed in Beijing said he escaped
by hiding under timber in the back of a truck, a London newspaper
reported Sunday.
   The Sunday Express reported that Wu'er Kaixi, 21, and his
girlfriend, student activist Liu Yan, 19, were now living on the
outskirts of Pasadena, Calif., in a hideout it claimed was guarded
by the CIA.
   It said We`er was interviewed Friday at the hideout.
   The newspaper quoted Wu`er as saying that his escape was aided
by Hong Kong students and the CIA. It did not disclose any further
details of his escape.
   The Express said Wu`er predicted that China's communist
leadership would be toppled within three years ``if an incident
does not provoke it sooner.''
   If 84-year-old Deng Xiaoping, China's senior leader, dies soon,
``it could be a signal for the people to come out on the streets
again,'' Wu`er was quoted as saying. The demonstrations in
Beijing's Tiananmen Square were sparked by the death of former
Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang.
   Wu'er was quoted as saying that his network of contacts in China
estimate that 3,000 people were killed when the army stormed the
square on June 3-4, and that 120,000 have since been arrested or
executed.
   Xinhua, China's official news agency, has said nearly 100
soldiers and police died and that thousands were injured, while
about 100 civilians died and nearly 1,000 were injured. Chinese
witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may
have been as high as 3,000.
   Wu`er captured worldwide attention in a televised confrontation
between hunger-striking student leaders and Premier Li Peng in the
Forbidden City shortly before the army assault.
   ``I was just a student, out of hospital, but I had no fear of Li
Peng,'' he was quoted as saying. ``He is a devil but he did not
frighten me. I told him to start democratic reforms and not delay.''
   Wu`er said he was in the square when tanks rolled in.
   ``Students tried to reason with soldiers who were firing like
madmen, bayoneting young men and women,'' he was quoted as saying.
``I was put into an ambulance with two dead students ... As we sped
to hospital, I saw the tanks firing their machine guns into the
crowd.''
