<FIRST>u i AM-BerlinWall     08-12 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Berlin Wall,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany says Berlin Wall to Stay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany on Saturday defended the Berlin Wall,
built 28 years ago to block East Germans from fleeing to the West,
and said hopes for the removal of the barrier are ``illusory.''
   Neues Deutschland, the newspaper of the East German Communist
Party, said the wall is ``a step toward peace'' and repeated the
government stand that it will remain in place as long as the reason
for its construction exists.
   Sunday is the anniversary of the construction of the wall on
Aug. 13, 1961.
   President Bush issued a statement Saturday calling the wall
``the relic of a bygone era and a failed policy.''
   ``We observe this sad anniversary with renewed determination to
overcome the division of Berlin and of Europe,'' Bush said in the
statement from Camp David, Md. He said he hoped for a Soviet
response that would make Berlin, divided into East and West Berlin,
``a place of cooperation, not a point of confrontation.''
   In its commentary, Neues Deutschland accused the West of trying
to ``economically plunder and destabilize East Germany.''
   After World War II and the division of Germany, hundreds of
thousands of people fled from Soviet-controlled East Germany until
the concrete and barbed-wire wall was built. The East German
economy struggled and stumbled as workers, scientists, artists and
intellectuals escaped to the West.
   Once in West Germany, the East Germans qualify for immediate
citizenship and social assistance.
   Another flow of East German refugees has been moving recently
through communist Hungary, which has dismantled much of its border
barriers with Austria.
   East Germans can gain permission to travel to Hungary with
relative ease and an estimated 1,500 have gone to Hungary this
summer and then escaped through Austria into West Germany.
   As many as 400 other East Germans are seeking refuge at West
German embassies in Budapest, Prague and East Berlin and seeking
exit visas. West Germany has allowed them to stay in the embassies
but on Tuesday it closed the doors of its East Berlin mission
saying it was crowded and could not accommodate any more people.
   Last week, officials of both East and West Germany were
encouraging the East Germans to return home and seek legal means of
emigrating.
</TEXT>
