<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Willinger     08-12 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Willinger,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laszlo Willinger, Hollywood Photographer, Dead at 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian-born photographer Laszlo Willinger,
who profiled such stars of Hollywood's golden era as Joan Crawford
and Clark Gable, died of heart failure, his publisher said
Saturday. He was 83.
   Willinger died at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center on Tuesday, said
publisher Edward Weston.
   A professional photographer since he was 16, Willinger devoted
his career to taking pictures of illustrious personalities, and was
recognized as one of Hollywood's top photographers.
   ``The only thing that was expected of me was to make images that
the press would choose to print over everyone else's,'' Willinger
said in an interview last year. ``You must realize that there were
5,000 pictures available on any major star. To get printed, yours
had to be the best.''
   Willinger was born in Budapest, Hungary, on April 16, 1906.
While a teen he ran his first studio in Berlin. At 19 he went to
Paris, where he managed the portrait studio of the Keystone Agency,
also known as the Talbot Studios.
   He opened his own studio in Vienna, Austria, when he was 23.
Among his European subjects were Sigmund Freud, Maurice Chevalier
and Josephine Baker.
   But with war brewing, Willinger left Europe for Hollywood in
1937 and joined MGM studios.
   ``I don't think that at any time in history more people so
talented on every level had ever come together as in the Hollywood
of those decades,'' Willinger said of the 1930s and 1940s.
   Willinger said his favorite photo subjects were Miss Crawford,
Vivien Leigh and Gable. ``They knew what was expected of them,''
Willinger said. ``These stars not only cooperated, they were eager.
Some actors didn't understand this, and you never heard from them
again.''
   Willinger left MGM in 1944 and shot stock photography and
advertising. He worked for 40 years with FPG, a New York photo
agency that stocked some 50,000 of Willinger's transparencies.
   Willinger is survived by his wife, Yvonne. Funeral arrangements
were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890812-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Shrimpers-Turtles     08-12 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shrimpers-Turtles,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Ticketed Under New Trawling Restrictions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard ticketed six shrimpers
for violating new trawling-time restrictions intended to keep sea
turtles from drowning, authorities said Saturday.
   Five shrimpers in Galveston and one in Freeport were issued
citations for trawling without turtle excluder devices during
30-minute restricted periods, said Coast Guard spokesman Don Merwin.
   The new regulations being rigorously enforced since Friday night
require shrimpers to limit trawling to 105-minute intervals as
outlined by a Coast Guard time chart or use the devices, which are
designed to allow sea turtles to escape from shrimping nets.
   The devices are big boxes attached to nets with hinged sides
that turtles can swim through.
   Shrimpers who elect not to use the devices have to pull their
nets from the water during the 30-minute intervals when trawling is
prohibited.
   ``I would think that a vessel that has its nets in the water
during those periods will be a good candidate for boarding,'' Coast
Guard spokesman Nicholas Sandifer said in Washington.
   The Coast Guard has been broadcasting the time schedules and is
warning shrimpers before each 30-minute ban goes into effect,
Merwin said.
   Shrimpers out during the 30-minute intervals are being asked to
pull in their nets for inspection. Those without the devices are
fined.
   The maximum fine for a first and second offense is $8,000. The
maximum fine for a third offense is $12,000. Fines are levied by
the National Marines Fisheries Service, Merwin said.
   The Coast Guard is patrolling areas from Cameron, La., to
Freeport.
   The order to enforce the limited trawling option was issued at 6
p.m. Thursday. Three hours later, the captain of a shrimping vessel
off the Florida coast was cited after a Coast Guard boarding crew
observed that it was trawling illegally, Coast Guard officials said.
   Shrimpers who have fought against using the excluder devices are
concerned that the regulations implemented by U.S. Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher are so complicated they will be hard to
follow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890812-0123 </DOCNO>
