<SECOND>AM-Eastwood-People,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tabloid Makes His Day; Clint Eastwood Accepts Libel Damages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clint Eastwood has accepted undisclosed libel
damages from a British tabloid newspaper that reported Sunday it
had published false reports about the actor's private life.
   Eastwood accepted an apology for libelous articles published in
the News of the World on July 9 and ``a large sum'' in libel
damages and legal fees, said a statement agreed to by the actor and
News Group Newspapers.
   The amount of the settlement was not disclosed.
   Eastwood, who is in London completing a movie titled ``White
Hunter, Black Heart,'' said Saturday that the newspaper ``has
recognized its mistake and I appreciate that.''
   ``The apology was the most important thing to me,'' he said. ``I
didn't embark on this to make a profit, and whatever money I end up
with after all this I shall donate to charities.''
   Eastwood's lawyers issued a writ against the newspaper on
Friday. An apology published in Sunday editions of the country's
top-selling weekly tabloid said the articles were ``untrue and
should not have been published.''
   It was the latest in a series of libel awards by British
publications, particularly the racier tabloids, on wrong or
unprovable stories about the private lives of well-known
personalities.
   In the biggest such award, the tabloid Sun in December was
ordered to pay rock singer Elton John $1.75 million.
