<FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-89 2245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Ashura     08-12 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Ashura,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Shiites Commemorate Holy Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphotos BEI5,6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Shiite Moslems in
southern Lebanon commemorated the holy day of Ashura Saturday with
many striking their heads with the flat edge of their swords or
chains until they drew blood.
   Ashura, marking the death in battle of Shiite saint Hussein in
A.D. 680, is the holiest day of the year for the world's 100
million Shiite Moslems.
   Scores of white-robed Shiites, bleeding from head wounds and
chanting religious verses, led a procession through Nabatiyeh.
   Iran, a Moslem country with fundamentalist Shiite leaders, will
commemorate Ashura Sunday.
   Ashura is derived from the Arabic word for the number 10. It
refers to the first 10 days of the first month of the Islamic lunar
calendar, Muharram, culminating in the tenth day, the day of
Hussein's death.
   The division of Islam into Shiite and Sunni groups developed
after the death in 632 of Mohammed, the founder of the faith.
Mohammed's closest followers determined that his companion, Abu
Bakr, be declared the next leader of Islam.
   A minority of Moslems challenged the dicision and argued that
the leadership should be dynastic and should therefore have gone to
Ali, the son-in-law and cousin of Mohammed, who had no sons.
   Ali did become leader but after his death in 661, a dynasty
known as the Ummayids and based in Syria declared it was the ruler
of Islam.
   Hussein, the son of Ali, challenged the Ummayid rule and the
Ummayids representing the mainstream Sunnis sought to crush
Hussein's movement.
   In 680, the Ummayid forces surrounded Hussein and his followers
and killed them in a battle at Kerbala, about 100 miles south of
Baghdad in modern Iraq.
   But the victory did not crush the Shiites and Hussein's death
added an element of passion to Shiism, which venerates martyrdom.
   Shiites follow the same major rules and rites as the Sunni
Moslem majority of about 800 million, including five prayers a day,
the pilgrimage to Mecca, and fasting in the holy month of Ramadan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
