<FIRST>r a AM-Newspage-BirdContract     08-12 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage-Bird Contract,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Larry Bird to Become First Pro Athlete to Earn $6 Million for One
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Celtics' Larry Bird, who missed nearly all of
the National Basketball Association's last season, will become the
first professional athlete in any team sport to earn more than $6
million in a single year, sources told the Associated Press on
Saturday.
   Bird, 32, negotiated the sum before undergoing surgery on his
feet in October with two years left in his five-year contract. He
had been earning $1.8 million a year, far less than the $3
million-plus of such NBA players as Michael Jordan of Chicago and
Patrick Ewing of the New York Knicks.
   The negotiations were complicated by the NBA's salary cap, which
will be $9.8 million per team this year. The Celtics reportedly
agreed to a two-year contract extension under which Bird's salary
and bonus will jump to between $6 million and $7 million during the
1991-92 season.
   Bird's agent and attorney, Bob Woolf, confirmed Saturday that
the 6-foot-9 forward had signed an extension through 1991-92. Bird
and Celtics general manager Jan Volk were not available for comment.
   Bird, a nine-time All-Star, led the Celtics to three NBA titles
in the 1980s. He has averaged nearly 25 points per game in his
10-year career.
</TEXT>
