<FIRST>r a AM-BlindRobbery     08-12 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blind Robbery,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blind Man Will Face Lesser Charges in Bank Holdup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind man who said he held up a bank
after losing his Social Security money will not be prosecuted for
bank robbery but for a lesser charge of burglary and grand theft,
authorities said.
   Richard Dunbar, 34, was arrested for investigation of holding up
a downtown Bank of America branch of $950 on Thursday.
   Dunbar told police he became desperate after public agencies
were unable to help him when he lost his government check, said
officers who questioned the man.
   He told police he planned to use the money to buy food and pay
for overnight shelter.
   ``It was a choice between robbing the bank or killing myself,''
said Dunbar. ``I was at the end of my rope and I was frightened.''
   Dunbar will be charged with second-degree burglary and grand
theft when he is arraigned Monday, Jerome Benson, chief of the
district attorney's criminal division, said Friday.
   Authorities decided to charge Dunbar with the lesser crimes
because of the circumstances and the man's blindness, Benson said.
   Both charges could be reduced to misdemeanors, the prosecutor
said. Bank robbery is a felony that carries a sentence of two to
five years.
   Dunbar was being held in the city jail.
   According to police accounts of the robbery, Dunbar handed a
teller a note demanding money. Another employee slipped out of the
bank and called a police officer.
   It was not until Dunbar was arrested at gunpoint that officers
and the teller realized he was blind, Benson said. Dunbar was not
armed.
