<FIRST>u i AM-Maldives 1stLd-Writethru   08-12 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maldives, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0590,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maldives Coup Leader, 15 Others Sentenced to Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th pvs, `The Maldivian...' to ADD dropped words ``were
members of;'' picks up 7th pvs, `Chief Justice...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high court in the Maldives on
Saturday sentenced a Sri Lanka-based Maldivian businessman to death
for leading a failed coup in the Indian Ocean archipelago, the
Maldivian government said.
   Seventy-five people, including 68 Sri Lankan Tamil mercenaries,
were convicted of participating in the Nov. 3, 1988 coup attempt.
Sixteen people, four Maldivians and 12 Sri Lankans, were given
death sentences. The other 59 received prison terms ranging from
nine to 38 years.
   The condemned men will be hanged, said Ahmed Saleem, deputy
director of the Maldives Information and Broadcasting Department.
   ``Everybody here feels those guilty of this grave crime must be
severely dealt with, there should be no leniency,'' Saleem said by
telephone.
   The court found businessman Abdullah Luthufi guilty of
organizing the attempt to overthrow President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom.
The attempt was crushed by Indian paratroopers after Gayoom
requested help. At least 17 people, mostly local residents, were
killed in the fighting.
   The Maldivian government has said the convicted Sri Lankans were
mercenaries who were members of a Tamil separatist group.
   Chief Justice Moosa Fathy, heading a three-judge panel, read the
sentences at a hearing after nearly two months of trial.
   No dates were set for the execution.
   The court has asked the convicted men to pay $14 million as
compensation for deaths, injuries and property damage, the
government statement said.
   There is no higher court of appeal in Maldives, a string of
coral islands in the Indian Ocean. Only President Gayoom can
commute the sentences. The last death sentence in Maldives was
carried out in 1951 by a firing squad.
   The Maldives archipelago is about 500 miles southwest of Sri
Lanka and roughly the same distance south of India. The country is
made up of about 2,000 islands, but only about 200 are inhabited.
</TEXT>
