<FIRST>r a AM-Floods 1stLd-Writethru a0556 08-12 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Floods, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Inundate East Coast, Southern California Advised to Conserve
Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with mudslide at Yellowstone National
Park, flooding in Colorado, CORRECT that 10 inches of rain fell on Long
Island on Friday, sted Saturday; Picks up 6th graf pvs, `That word...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents on both coasts coped with summer downpours Saturday as
New Yorkers slogged through ankle-deep water and Southern
Californians were told to be ``water tight'' while an aqueduct is
repaired.
   Thunderstorms last week that tore up the aqueduct that supplies
three-quarters of Los Angeles' water also damaged hundreds of homes
in California and Arizona. On Saturday, Eastern storms flooded
roads, small streams, subway tunnels and the roof of a Hartford,
Conn., apartment building where collapsing ceilings chased out
eight families.
   ``I've lost everything _ my furniture, my clothes, my car,''
said Santiago Caballero, a 63-year-old unemployed farmworker who
said he saved for 10 years to buy his modest home in Yuma, Ariz.,
across the state line from Southern California.
   Another mudslide was reported at Yellowstone National Park in
Wyoming, one mile west of where 15 mudslides occurred two days ago.
   Colorado Springs, Colo., reported street flooding from 3 inches
of rain that fell during an hour and a half. One parking lot was
under 2 feet of water and many cars were stranded.
   A stationary front along the middle and northern Atlantic coast
brought the torrential rain in the New York City area, with 2.9
inches from midnight to 3 p.m. Up to 10 inches of rain fell Friday
at the eastern end of Long Island, the National Weather Service
reported.
   More than an inch of rain fell in one hour in New York early
Saturday morning and again in an afternoon hour, but the amounts
were well short of the one-hour record of over 2 inches set in
1983, said meteorologist Ben Scott.
   That word would have provided little solace, however, to
thousands of New York pedestrians who found themselves wrapped in
sheets of falling water or to subway riders whose packed trains
were stalled by power shutoffs caused by the flooding.
   Suburban travelers had problems too. In Pelham Manor just north
of the city, 6.66 inches fell between midnight and 3 p.m., closing
roads.
   Up to 5 inches of rain fell in the New Haven, Conn., area before
tapering off around 4:30 p.m. Friday, said Todd Mendell, a
hydrologist at the River Forecast Center in Hartford.
   Firefighters found 5,000 gallons of water collecting on the roof
of a Hartford apartment builing where several ceilings collapsed
Friday.
   ``When we found the water was coming down through the ceiling
into the light fixtures we called the building department and began
to shut off the power and the building department suggested we
evacuate the building,'' said firefighter Lester McBride.
   Forecasters said rain could continue through the weekend on the
affected parts of the East Coast and in Southern California.
   Since Wednesday, widely scattered downpours have inundated areas
from San Diego to Las Vegas, as well as Arizona's Yuma County.
   A 1,000-foot stretch of the huge Los Angeles Aqueduct, 180 miles
north of the city, buckled, cracked and popped Thursday after it
was flooded by heavy rains and clogged with debris.
   Dennis Williams, a Los Angeles Department of Water and Power
engineer, said crews working around the clock would need about two
weeks to repair the aqueduct. Repairs could take longer if it
continues to rain, he said.
   ``What we're asking is that everyone take to heart our
conservation program and be water tight,'' said Rich Atwater,
director of resources for the Metropolitan Water District of
Southern California.
   The repairs were expected to cost at least $500,000, and highway
damage in the Sierra Nevada was reported at more than $1 million.
   Affected residents spent Friday and Saturday pumping water and
shoveling mud from homes.
   ``We're not going to recover from these storms for a long, long
time,'' Yuma police spokesman Jan Schmidt said. ``We were totally
underwater.''
   Some of the most serious damage was done to agriculture, Mono
County, Calif., sheriff's spokeswoman Gail Merritt said.
   ``There's some folks over there with a huge field of garlic just
ready to pick and it's all gone,'' said Benton farmer Bud Orris.
</TEXT>
