<FIRST>r a AM-CorneaLawsuit     08-12 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cornea Lawsuit,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Dismissed on Removal of Dead Man's Corneas Against Family
Wishes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coroner may have acted callously in removing
a dead man's corneas for transplant despite his family's
objections, but he did not violate anyone's rights, a federal judge
ruled.
   U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel on Friday dismissed a $1.5
million lawsuit against the Hamilton County coroner's office
brought by Steven Brotherton's survivors.
   The judge expressed concern at the coroner's ``arbitrary and
insensitive actions,'' but said he had no option but to dismiss the
lawsuit, which also named an eye bank and an organ procurement
center.
   Spiegel said the family was mistaken in making property claims
in the case, but told them they could sue in a state court in which
the defendants can be accused of causing severe emotional distress.
   Defendants in the lawsuit included the coroner, Dr. Frank
Cleveland, the Cincinnati Eye Bank for Sight Restoration and the
Ohio Valley Organ Procurement Center.
   Brotherton's wife, Deborah, refused Bethesda North Hospital's
request for an organ donation following her husband's death, saying
her husband was opposed to the practice.
   Cleveland later allowed a technician from the eye bank to remove
Brotherton's corneas, even though his wife's objections to organ
donations were included in hospital records of Brotherton's death.
   Clear corneas from dead people are used in transplant operations
to replace corneas that are clouded by cataracts.
   Spiegel said the hospital made no effort to relay Deborah
Brotherton's objections to Cleveland. He also said the coroner
routinely allows removal of corneas without looking at medical
records or documents belonging to the dead people from whom the
corneas are taken.
   Cleveland was not available for comment.
</TEXT>
