<FIRST>u a AM-HUD-Democrats     08-12 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Democrats,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: HUD Pattern of Favoritism Not Confined to GOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While well-connected Republicans received
political favors from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development, Democrats also benefited, according to a report in The
New York Times.
   Democrats did not realize financial benefits as big as some GOP
members, but former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce's favoritism was
not limited to his own party, the Times reported in Sunday editions.
   ``Believe me, it wasn't just Republicans at this party,'' an
unidentified senior housing official told the Times.
   In one example the Times cited, a political supporter and friend
of U.S. Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Texas, was awarded a $5 million grant
and federal subsidies for 500 apartments.
   Brooks was head of the Government Operations Committee, which
monitors federal agencies.
   The Times said that in the last three years HUD awarded millions
of dollars in grants from a discretionary fund to projects in the
home districts of U.S. Reps. Thomas Foley, D-Wash., who was then
majority leader; Tony Coelho, D-Calif., former majority whip, and
Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee.
   None of the awards was illegal, the newspaper said.
   Republican consultants, developers and members of Congress
secured favors from HUD by appealing to the political loyalties of
HUD managers, the Times said.
   Democratic representatives also approached HUD officials for
grants and subsidies, but more often they took advantage of their
majority in Congress by imposing their wishes on housing
appropriations bills, the Times said.
</TEXT>
