<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-12 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reform Communists Denounce 1968 Invasion of Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Hungarian reform communists
published a statement Saturday condemning the Soviet-led invasion
of Czechslovakia in 1968 that crushed a liberal communist
government.
   A statement in the Communist Party newspaper Nepszabadsag from
the reform group in the city of Debrecen called on the party's
Central Committee and the government ``to condemn ... the forcible
intervention'' by the Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact allies,
including Hungary, 21 years ago.
   The statement said the group also agreed with a declaration
being circulated in Czechoslovakia urging the release of political
prisoners.
   ``We are closely following the attempts of the democratic forces
in today's Czechoslovakia,'' the statement said.
   The Czechoslovak leadership has said people signing the
declaration face fines and imprisonment. But Czechoslovak sources
in the West say at least 15,000 people have signed the proclamation.
   The Debrecen statement came nine days before the 21st
anniversary of the invasion. Imre Szokai, Hungary's deputy chief of
international relations with other communist parties, on Friday
said the invasion was ``essentially wrong.'' Czechoslovakia is a
member of the Warsaw Pact. With the exception of Romania, all other
members _ the Soviet Union, Bulgaria, East Germany, Hungary and
Poland _ participated in the invasion.
   Six independent Czechoslovak groups plan peaceful marches and
silent protests on the Aug. 21 anniversary of the invasion to voice
their desire for ``freedom, democracy and human rights,'' an emigre
source in Vienna said Saturday.
   Palach Press, a newsletter published in London by Czechoslovak
emigres, reported the six groups were circulating a statement that
said:
   ``The approaching Aug.21 is a source of concern for many
responsible and level-headed people among us.
   ``The past year has shown clearly that Czechoslovak citizens no
longer wish just to wait, especially since major changes for the
better are taking place around us.
   ``It is ... to be expected that this year many people will wish
to express their disagreement.''
   The changes it referred to are reforms under way in the Soviet
Union and some Soviet-bloc countries including Hungary and Poland.
   The six groups circulating the statement were not identified.
</TEXT>
